Germany is the first in Europe to introduce an "indefinite gender" when registering children
Germany will be the first country in Europe to allow the registration of children born hermaphrodites, instead of male or female to indicate "indefinite".
The child's parents will have the right to leave the "gender" column on the birth certificate blank for a while.
Instead of "F" (female) or "M" (male), parents can temporarily write down "X" (indefinite).
This decision is aimed at not pushing parents to rush to the operation to "clarify" gender.
According to statistics, one in 2 thousand newborns in the world is born with a hermaphrodite.
Anger over the verdict of the organizers of the terrorist attack in Bali
Survivors and relatives of the 202 victims of a 2002 Bali bombing reacted angrily to the sentence handed down to the last of the conspirators, who was brought to trial, and said that Umar Patek should be shot.
Patek, who spent nearly 10 years on the run as one of Southeast Asia's most wanted men, was sentenced yesterday to 20 years in prison for his role in building explosive devices used in the attack.
He can be released for 15 years if he receives parole.
The 45-year-old defendant was found guilty of mass murder in an attack on two nightclubs in the popular tourist area of Kuta, during which 202 people died, including 88 Australians, and injured dozens more.
He was also found guilty on a number of other terrorism-related charges, including a wave of church bombings across Indonesia on Christmas Eve in 2000.
Prosecutors have demanded a life sentence, although they could have insisted that the man, nicknamed the "subversive" for his reputation as an explosive device maker, should be sentenced to death.
The decision exacerbated the painful memories of Perth mother June Cortin, who lost her 39-year-old twin daughters Jane and Jenny in a terrorist attack carried out by Patek and his accomplices nearly a decade ago.
Barely holding back tears, she said that Patek should have been sentenced to death.
"I really believe he should follow in the footsteps of other guys.
He must appear before the firing squad," Ms Cortin told the AAP.
"I have to live every day knowing that I will no longer have grandchildren and I will not see my daughters."
Club Sari was destroyed when a massive explosive device planted in a van parked outside was detonated just after 11 p.m. on 12 October 2002.
Peter Hughes had been at paddy's bar, where a suicide bomber had detonated a backpack packed with explosives just 20 seconds earlier.
After this terrorist attack, he fell into a coma for a month and "died" three times, being connected to the life support system.
Mr Hughes said Patek should share the fate of three other members of the Jemaah Islamiyah terrorist cell responsible for the carnage , Amrozi, Mukhlas and Imam Samoudra, who were executed four years ago.
Indeed, this guy deserves the death penalty the most.
Save his life, well, there's no reason to save his life.
Getting 20 years after killing 202 people and injuring hundreds is not that much.
Patek is the latest participant in the Bali attack to stand trial.
He went into hiding for nearly a decade but was eventually detained in January 2011 in the Pakistani city of Abbottabad, where U.S. troops killed former al-Qaeda leader Osama bin Laden less than four months later.
During the trial, the FBI agent testified that intelligence evidence showed That Patek was in Pakistan to meet with bin Laden in an attempt to re-establish ties between Southeast Asian terrorist groups and al-Qaeda.
"He didn't give up," Ms Cortin said.
Until recently, he didn't regret how much grief he caused to other people.
The verdict comes ahead of the 10th anniversary of the attack, which will be celebrated later this year in Bali and Australia.
"There will be a lot of tears this year," says Ms. Cortin.
Patek can still appeal his verdict.
