Power engineers of Dnipropetrovsk region have launched a unique program to save... stork nests
In the old days, in order to bring storks to the yard, villagers on a high pole installed a wheel from a cart, and a heavy nest was well held on it.
Such special supports have not been installed for a long time, so storks have chosen the poles of power lines - intertwined branches rely on wires, so that the stork house stands reliably.
Grandmother Anya, near whose house in the village of Ivanovka, Petrikovsky district, a stork family has been living for twenty years, began to notice how the nest settles, despite all the efforts of its inhabitants.
Birds put new twigs on top, and the bottom layer has already sagged between the wires, about to collapse.
Of course, I feel sorry for the family of storks who nested every year at the farmstead, bred and fed three or four chicks during the summer, but they do not want to remain without light.
As soon as the birds flew to warm lands, Grandmother Anya called the Tsarichansky RES, which owns the support.
And I did not even expect that they would react so quickly.
When our specialists arrived in Ivanovka, they were surprised that the nest was still holding at all," said Sergey Berezovsky, Technical Director of DTEK Dniprooblenergo.
On the wires, which were, in fact, already inside the socket, weighing 150 - 200 kilograms, corrosion began.
At any time, birds could die from an electric discharge.
And the locals risked being left without light due to damage to the wires.
Therefore, linear fitters have launched an operation to save the nest, and not for the first time in our practice.
Ornithologists from Dnipropetrovsk National University helped, who developed a scheme for transferring the nest.
They also conducted trainings for employees of district networks.
Well-known Dnepropetrovsk ornithologist Alexander Ponomarenko advised power engineers at all stages of nest reconstruction.
To begin with, it was estimated that more than 50 stork "apartments" are in disrepair in the region.
For their reconstruction, special metal platforms resembling a funnel were welded.
The base was braided with willow branches, and then the old nest was moved there.
According to experts, it is enough to lay old branches as a basis so that the birds recognize the nest and return to it.
Only then will the storks finish their own home.
A month ago, in the village of Peschanka, Novomoskovsk District, the first nest was reconstructed.
A new reinforced concrete pole was placed next to the electric pole and a platform with an old, already inhabited nest was placed on it.
The whole operation cost the power engineers nine thousand hryvnias.
And the other day the same housewarming party took place in the village of Ivanovka, Petrikovsky district, on the farmstead of Ani's grandmother.
Here, the platform was fixed in the same place, only raised above the wires.
Ornithologists are sure that cautious, conservative birds will not even notice in the spring that their "apartment" has undergone major repairs.
By the end of the year, the same reconstruction awaits four more nests in the Pokrovsky and Tsarichansky districts of the Dnipropetrovsk region.
By the way, while some save rare birds, others ruthlessly kill them.
The other day, sad news flew around the whole region - in the village of Ust-Kamenka of the Apostolovsky district, on the day of the opening of the pheasant hunt, poachers for the sake of entertainment shot a swan family that lived on a local pond.
Noble birds were not afraid of people at all - the locals fed them and did not offend them.
When the villagers, hearing the shots, ran to the pond, four handsome swans were already lying on the water dead.
Now employees of the Apostolovsky district police department are finding out who shot at the birds listed in the Red Book.
Stuck in Chita American Boeing is preparing for departure
Conducting observation flights over the territory of Russia within the framework of the Treaty on Open Skies and making an unscheduled landing in Chita on Wednesday, an American plane will leave the city's air harbor on Friday, November 1, at 8:30 Moscow time.
The airport management allowed the departure of the board, having received money for fuel.
As reported at the airport, the plane will fly to Ulan-Ude.
According to other sources, he will go to the United States.
As reported, the plane flying to Ulan-Ude landed in the Trans-Baikal Territory due to fog.
Due to unpaid bills, he was not allowed out of the Chita airport.
On board the plane are 30 people, including the crew, they spent two nights on the territory of the airport, reports ITAR-TASS.
According to the Russian Foreign Ministry, according to the terms of the Treaty on Open Skies, people on board the aircraft do not have the right to leave the Chita airport, they can pass border control only at two Russian airports - in Kubinka and in Ulan-Ude.
The Treaty on Open Skies was signed in 1992, it involves 34 states.
Observation flights are made over the territories of Russia, the USA, Canada, and European countries.
The main objectives of the Treaty are to develop transparency, promote the monitoring of the implementation of agreements in the field of arms control, expand opportunities for crisis prevention and crisis management within the framework of the OSCE and other international organizations.
