Cocaine-addicted lawyer who warned the ringleader of a criminal gang about a police investigation has been jailed
42-year-old Basharat Ditta passed information to crime boss Neil Scarborough
The lawyer was afraid that his secret drug addiction would be revealed.
He was sentenced to three years' imprisonment by the Royal Court of Liverpool.
A prestigious lawyer who told a drug lord about a major police investigation because he feared exposing his secret drug addiction was jailed for three years.
Basharat Dittah, 42, gave crime boss Neil Scarborough classified information about his drug trafficking investigation after being threatened by his cocaine addiction.
The lawyer, nicknamed Bash and nicknamed the "tough lawyer" among criminals, was arrested at his home in 2011 after a police operation to spy on Scarborough, whom he had previously represented at a drug-related trial.
Officers noticed Scarborough, 32, leaving three bags of cocaine outside a lawyer's home in Blackburn, Lancashire, while he was at a bar association dinner with colleagues.
Investigators revealed that Ditta "regularly used" a Class A drug after tests showed traces of cocaine in his hair, on his wallet and on credit cards.
For eight months from January to August 2011, he tried to illegally obtain information about the arrests of two people on behalf of Scarborough, as well as one of his accomplices.
All four suspects were under police surveillance at the time as part of a major investigation into a criminal heroin and cocaine trafficking organization in Lancashire, Cumbria, Merseyside, Berkshire and West Yorkshire.
They and 32 others were later jailed after police seized £1.5 million worth of heroin and cocaine in a series of raids, as well as more than £200,000 in cash.
Ditta, 42, passed on information to criminals out of fear that his cocaine addiction would be exposed.
At Liverpool Royal Court, Ditt, who works for Blackburn-based Forbes Solicitors, was now in shambles after being found guilty of two counts of intentional obstruction of justice following a three-week trial at Liverpool Crown Court.
He confessed to possession of cocaine at a previous court hearing.
The lawyer's exposure came after police investigating Scarborough found out that he had been talking to Ditt on the phone regularly since February 2011.
Two detectives followed the suspect and discovered how he approached Ditt's home in Blackburn and placed 60 per cent clean drugs in a black golf glove under the lawyer's trash cans.
Shortly after the pass, Scarborough repeatedly called Ditt, who was at dinner at Blackburn Rovers' Ewood Park football stadium.
The lawyer returned home for drugs; nine conversations took place between them.
The court learned that Ditt had "regularly used" cocaine after tests found traces of the Class A drug in his hair, wallet and credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested but denied using cocaine, said he had spoken to the suspect dealer because he was his client, and insisted that their communication constituted "attorney-client privilege."
During his arrest, Ditta took his wallet and tried to take out several credit cards, but all of them were confiscated, and a hair sample was also taken from him.
When questioned by police, he said that along with his workplace, he had a home office and clients came to his house on legal matters.
However, the court learned that after important arrests, he called the largest participants in drug trafficking, a number of whom he had previously represented in court, to tell what detectives knew about them.
In an accusatory speech, Anne White said, "If anyone knows not to break the law, it's a criminal defense attorney."
Mr. Ditta is accused of abusing his position as a criminal lawyer because he has entered into too close a relationship with certain clients.
The contact we are talking about is not just a drug dealer, but a drug dealer supplying drugs to his own lawyer.
Some of his conversations will certainly prove legitimate, as he was their lawyer.
However, this has largely crossed the boundaries of the normal attorney-client relationship.
He obstructed the police investigation as much as possible to allow these individuals to continue their criminal activities.
Mr. Ditta did not honor his profession, but disgraced it.
He became too close to certain clients, particularly Scarborough, and allowed his disinterest to be questioned.
Ditta pleaded not guilty and said: "If I were a corrupt lawyer, which I am not, and I wanted to pass on the information to Mr Scarborough, I would not have waited 15 hours, I would have done so immediately."
But after the hearing, Senior Officer Lee Halstead of Lancashire Police said: "Mr. Ditta went from a criminal lawyer to a felon as soon as he started buying drugs from organized crime."
His addiction to cocaine had made him hopelessly compromised and vulnerable to the targeting of key members of criminal gangs, who had tasked him with obtaining valuable information about police investigations.
Lawyers must follow the highest standards of professional ethics and instill trust and confidence in the public.
Mr. Ditta betrayed that trust and tried to hide behind his profession.
Mr. Ditt was investigated by the Lancashire Unit for Particularly Dangerous Organized Crime, which had already secured his conviction in three cases of cocaine possession and now in obstruction of justice, demonstrating our desire to obtain fair punishment for the perpetrators.
Let this case serve as a warning to criminals that no one is beyond the reach of the law.
We will find you and bring you to justice.
Scarborough himself was sentenced to 14 years after pleading guilty to conspiring to supply heroin, cocaine and marijuana.
Another 35 people involved in the fraud were sentenced to a total of 153 years for drug-related crimes.
On his website, Ditt organized a Q&A talk in which he says his dream job is a lawyer representing death sentence clients in America, the perfect companion for him over dinner is Muhammad Ali, and the motivation to work is inequality.
Jet manufacturers feud over seat width when big orders are at stake
A bitter dispute has erupted between leading aircraft manufacturers over the width of tourist class seats on long-haul flights, setting the tone for a fierce confrontation at this month's Dubai Aviation Expo.
The dispute revolves around the width of seats provided on long-haul flights to economy class passengers, whose interests are not always at the forefront of the attention of airlines, while the amount of space allocated to them plays a key role in the statements about the effectiveness of the latest aircraft offered by Airbus SAS and Boeing Co.
Airbus this week called for an industry standard that would provide for a seat width of at least 18 inches (46 cm) in economy class cabins, but its main U.S. rival Boeing says it's up to airlines to decide.
The dispute comes at a time when aircraft manufacturers are competing in sales of increasingly large versions of their twin-engine long-haul aircraft, and potentially record orders are expected at the Nov. 17-21 event.
The rear layout of the aircraft — especially whether 9 or 10 people are sitting in a row — is central to statements about the cost-effectiveness of new "mini-Airbus" projects.
Boeing claims that its updated 777X will seat 406 people, based on seats in the economy class more than 17 inches wide, placed 10 in each row.
Airbus says a rival version of its A350 will carry 350 people in economy class in 18-inch-wide seats arranged 9 in a row.
The giants of the aircraft industry often exchange blows on technical issues with the help of advertising in the professional press.
And now Airbus is speaking directly to the public ahead of the Dubai Air Show, where the 777X is expected to be the leader with more than 100 orders.
She recently demonstrated what the start of a new advertising war might be like by showing financiers a slide depicting three people in a restaurant snuggled up against each other, titled "Would you agree to this?"
"Boeing offers long-haul flights on seats narrower than those of regional turboprop aircraft," said Airbus sales manager John Leahy.
With the change in diet, people gain weight, but airplane seats have not changed dramatically.
Between the early 1970s, when the wide-body Boeing 747 set the standard for modern long-distance travel, and the turn of the century, the weight of the average American man between the ages of 40 and 49 increased by 10 percent, according to the U.S. Department of Health.
The waist circumference of the average 21st-century American man is 39.7 inches, according to statistics from the U.S. Health Service.
Airbus claims that its competitor adheres to the concept of seating in the 1950s, when the average waist circumference of those recently dubbed the "jet public" was narrower.
Airbus says it has commissioned a study showing that an extra inch in seat width improves sleep quality by 53 percent.
Boeing disputes Airbus' seat size figures and says manufacturers shouldn't interfere with decisions about how airlines find a balance between fares and amenities.
According to her, studies show that the convenience of the cabin depends not only on the width of the seat.
"It really comes down to giving airlines the choice and opportunity to do what they think they need to do to succeed," said Boeing cabin specialist Kent Craver.
They don't want us to decide for them what will make a profit for them.
They know their stuff better than anyone else.
For passengers, the issue is to increase the space on the sides, but for suppliers, this is increasingly becoming a factor that can affect profits.
Behind this dispute is a race for aircraft orders valued at at least $700 billion at catalog prices in the coming decades — enough to change the balance between U.S. and European exports.
As Reuters first reported in July, the seating arrangement is exactly what fuels the rivalry in the battle between the newest jets.
Both Airbus and Boeing claim a 20 percent increase in profitability by one seat in their latest twin-engine long-haul models compared to the market leader in this segment, the 365-seat Boeing 777-300ER.
Boeing's claimed performance is based in part on a comparison of the 10-seater 777X rows with the original 9-seater layout of the 777 series.
The gain in unit cost is reduced when compared to the 10-seat layout currently in use.
"The reason Boeing is doing this is to squeeze in more seats and make its aircraft more competitive compared to our designs," said Kevin Keniston, Airbus' head of passenger comfort in Europe.
On the other hand, analysts say saloons with full 10-seater rows for the existing 777s indicate that many passengers prefer a tight seating arrangement that can go hand-in-hand with lower fares.
"Eighteen-inch-wide seats would be ideal for passengers, but the reality is that from a commercial point of view, Airbus' offering is driven by the threat from the 777 model," said interior specialist Mary Kirby, founder and editor of the Runway Girl Network.
Airbus and Boeing do not supply seats, but offer a catalog of suppliers from which airlines can choose.
Traveling around the world, jet sellers even carry tape measures with them to check on competing layouts.
Touting comfort, all manufacturers also offer aircraft with a very dense cabin layout for low-cost airlines and regional flights.
Airbus is offering the A350 with 10-seater rows, but says it hasn't sold it yet.
Until recently, Airbus stressed the need for additional cabin modifications, offering wider aisle seats on some of its aircraft.
Without the support of the only other manufacturer of large modern aircraft, experts say, its call for a new industry standard is unlikely to "take off", but may distract attention from the wave of sales of the 777X model.
Oleynikov: a third of rural settlements in the Moscow region are fully subsidized
Vice-Governor of the Moscow region Yuri Oleynikov said that almost a third of the rural settlements of the Moscow region are completely subsidized
