Also in Mozhaisk, Kashirsky, Solnechnogorsk, Kolomensky districts, Lyubertsy and Kotelniki there is a request for consolidation of municipalities.
Discussion of this issue in the cities and districts of the region will begin in November.
Chairman of the Moscow City Duma Igor Bryntsalov also said that about 30 rural settlements in 12 districts of the Moscow region plan to unite in total within the framework of the upcoming administrative reform.
This is due to the fact that of the 178 rural settlements in the Moscow region, less than a third have an "acceptable" financial base, and 100 are subsidized.
Security concerns in Mozambique are growing as a result of a conflict of powerful people
Under a top-down statue of Zamora Machel, Mozambique's founding president, thousands of people gathered in central Maputo to chant peace slogans at one of the rare demonstrations here.
"We want peace back; we want stability," said Vanessa de Sousa, chief executive of the investment firm.
Fearing for the future of her country, she changed her business suit to a T-shirt emblazoned with the inscription "We demand security" in Portuguese, and joined the crowd on Thursday in the capital's Independence Square.
For two weeks, there have been near-daily reports of clashes between government forces and Renamo, one of the most violent clashes since the truce more than 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a prominent insurgency that was supported first by the white authorities of Rhodesia and then by the apartheid-era government of South Africa as part of efforts to destabilize the country's independent government.
After the 1992 armistice, it became an opposition party.
Analysts believe that the country is unlikely to slide back into a full-scale conflict, but recent events have made foreign investors and local residents nervous.
The stakes are high for a fast-growing economy, as the discovery of huge offshore gas reserves and coal deposits in the Northwest could raise more than $50 billion in investment over the next few years from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale of Brazil, Eni of Italy and Anadarko of the United States.
Frelimo's ruling party, the leading political force since 1975, and Renamo's party blame each other for the tensions.
Renamo's party claims the government was the instigator of the latest clashes by attacking its members in Sofala province, a traditional stronghold of Renamo, on Oct. 17.
Attacks on former rebels then escalated when government forces attacked Renamo bases and tried to kill Afonso Dhlakama, the group's leader, Fernando Mazanga, a renamo spokesman, told the Financial Times.
The government blames Renamo for initiating the clashes, accusing the party of attacking soldiers.
President Armandou Guebuza has tried to allay fears of instability.
Guebuza told AFP, a French news agency, on Wednesday that Mr Dhlakama felt like a "failure" who wanted to use "whatever was left of his strength to try to prove that he could impose his own solutions on the government".
Both Frelimo and Renamo insist they want to avoid war.
However, fears grew after it was reported that Mazanga announced Renamo's rejection of the 1992 peace agreement.
He told the Financial Times that he was referring to Frelimo's failure to comply with the agreement.
"Our goal is to return to negotiations, but with all seriousness," Mazanga said.
Previous talks between the parties have done little to ease tensions, which have been exacerbated by a series of clashes this year.
"These are two influential people (Gebuza and Dhlakama) facing foreheads," said Joseph Hanlon, a lecturer at the Open University and an expert on Mozambique.
None of them is a good negotiator and none of them is ready to make the necessary concessions.
Renamo's party, which is trying to push for electoral reforms, has already said it will boycott municipal elections scheduled for November.
Presidential and parliamentary elections are scheduled for next year.
Some commentators have interpreted this pressure as an attempt by a weakened movement to extract concessions and financial bonuses from the government.
The share of votes for Renamo has been declining since 1992, while a new party, the Mozambican Democratic Movement (MDM), which was founded by a former member of Renamo, is expected to improve its performance in these elections.
Mr. Mazanga said that Mr. Guebuza, who was due to step down next year when his second term ended, wanted to destroy democracy in the country.
"He doesn't want multiparty democracy, he doesn't want transparent elections, he doesn't want peace because he doesn't want to leave the presidency," Mazanga said.
It is unclear what capabilities Renamo has, but it has already carried out devastating and swift attacks on police stations and cars on a key highway leading from north to south.
Most of the skirmishes took place in Sofala province, which is a few hundred kilometers north of Maputo but includes Beira, a port that mining companies including Rio Tinto and Vale use to export coal.
In June, Rio suspended the use of railway tracks for about a week after Renamo threatened to attack the railway.
Mazanga was evasive when asked if Renamo would repeat the threat.
Renamo's party wanted to "warn the international community that things are not going well in Mozambique," Mazanga said.
Instability has heightened discontent with the government, and many people are also concerned about corruption, the slow pace of development and recent increased kidnappings, said Fernando Lima, head of the independent media company Mediacoop.
"People think that the responsibility for the future of the country lies with the government and the president, who must find a solution to these problems," he says.
Omar Sultuan, a participant in the demonstration, said people just want stability.
"Nobody cares about renamo or Frelimo, they just want the resumption of peace, they want free access to the roads," he said.
Rules for the use of electronic devices on aircraft in Australia will remain in force for the time being
Passengers of Australian airlines will need to continue to turn off their tablets and smartphones during takeoff and landing, despite measures in the United States to relax the rules regarding these devices.
The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration has allowed U.S. carriers to change their procedures so that passengers can read e-books, watch videos, or play games on their devices during takeoff and landing, provided they remain in "Airplane Mode."
Passengers can already do this during the main part of the flight, but many are annoyed that they do not have access to their e-books during takeoff and landing.
Australian carriers are considering the decision, which required U.S. airlines to do a huge amount of work to meet the new requirements, but have indicated that they have no plans to change their procedures in the near future.
The Civil Aviation Safety Authority also noted that they are considering this application, but stressed that restrictions on the use of electronic devices in critical phases of flight are still in force in Australia.
"The Civil Aviation Safety Authority currently has no special rules governing the use of electronic devices in aircraft," it said.
This issue is governed by regulations that require air carriers to maintain security at all times, and passengers to comply with safety rules reported to them by crew members.
Virgin, which has already discussed with the Civil Aviation Aviation Safety Authority the expansion of the use of its entertainment system with Wi-Fi on board, was not against the changes, but said that it would follow the instructions of the regulator.
"We would welcome consideration by the Civil Aviation Aviation Safety Authority of allowing the use of electronic devices because we really think it will improve the customer experience now that it (the on-board wireless entertainment system) is on our aircraft," the spokesperson said.
Qantas said it would adhere to the current rules.
"Our current policy is that electronic devices cannot be used during takeoff and landing, and we do not plan to change it in the near future," she said.
The FAA ruling applies to U.S. airlines.
Nevertheless, we are always interested in regulatory changes that could benefit passengers, and we will certainly carefully study the DECISION OF THE FAA and the reasons that caused it.
For U.S. carriers, the impact of the ruling will vary from airline to airline and will depend on the age of their fleet.
Carriers will have to prove that their aircraft are resistant to radio interference from mobile devices, as well as revise manuals, training materials, norms for carrying hand luggage and instructions for passengers.
"Once the airline has verified and confirmed the immunity of its fleet, it can allow passengers to use portable, lightweight electronic devices such as tablets, e-books and smartphones at any altitude," the FAA said.
In rare cases of poor visibility, the crew will instruct passengers to turn off their devices during boarding.
In addition, according to the group's recommendation, heavier devices should be located under the seats or in the upper luggage compartments during take-off and landing.
Obama retracts his words about health care
Amid a storm of criticism, President Obama backtracked yesterday on his oft-repeated, unequivocal promise that "if you like your health insurance plan, you can keep it."
Seeing hundreds of thousands of people receive service termination notices from their providers, Republicans have criticized the president in recent days for misleading the American public.
