Scientists have shed light on how the movements of a dog's tail are related to its mood.
Earlier studies have shown that satisfied dogs wag their tail to the right side (from the dog's point of view), while anxious dogs wave their tail predominantly to the left.
But now scientists say that other members of the canine family can notice these subtle differences in tail wagging and respond to them.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at Trent University, says: "It is well known that in humans the left and right sides of the brain are involved differently in the formation of motivators that cause positive or negative emotions."
Here we tried to look at this in other species as well.
He added that just like in humans, in dogs, the right side of the brain controls the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs respond to the versatile wagging of other dogs' tails, the researchers observed the animals as they watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the animals' heart rate and analyzed their behavior.
We will probably soon understand why their tails sometimes point in one direction and sometimes in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: "We showed the dogs videos of the dogs – either naturalistic versions or a silhouette – to get rid of any other distorting factors – and we could manipulate the movement of the tail and direct the tail more to the left or right. "
When the animals saw that the otherwise expressionless dog was moving its tail to the right (from the point of view of the wagging tail of the dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail was leaning predominantly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog wagging its tail), their heartbeat quickened and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he didn't think the dogs intentionally communicated with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that dogs have learned from their experiences which movements they should worry about and which they should not.
He observes, "If there are multiple encounters with other dogs and often the wagging of their tail in one direction is associated with more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, then the dog reacts based on this experience."
The researchers say these findings could give owners, veterinarians and trainers a deeper understanding of their animal's emotions.
Dog behaviour expert John Bradshaw, a visiting research fellow at the University of Bristol's Veterinary School, said this was not the first study to test whether the left and right sides matter to dogs.
Last year, a team of scientists from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when looking at an aggressive dog, and to the right if they look at a satisfied dog.
And in another study at the University of Victoria in Canada, he reported: "Dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when the wagging of its tail was directed to the left, rather than to the right, instead of becoming alarmed – the opposite behavior to the Italian study."
He said the differences could be due to the fact that dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in movies or robot dogs as dogs.
It could be useful to study how dogs react to real dogs, he explained.
"While there is ample evidence for different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details have yet to be clarified, and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, it is likely that we will soon understand why their tails sometimes point in one direction and sometimes in the other.
Are Europe's elite ready to do business with England?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with a commitment to bring together business representatives and determine what changes the creators of wealth and jobs in the UK want to see in relations with the EU.
To this end, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of British business leaders, asking them to express their thoughts on the UK, business and the EU.
YouGov surveyed more than 1,000 business leaders representing a broad cross-section of uk businesses by size, sector and region.
The findings of the survey will come as a surprise to many.
We found that the vast majority of businesses are now looking for export opportunities outside of Europe, with a particular focus on countries that are modernizing and growing while EU countries are stagnant.
They want the government to prioritize new trade ties with countries like China, India and Brazil, rather than wasting time on the long and arduous process of reforming the EU's intricate institutions.
When asked about their views on specific policy issues, from antitrust to product laws, most business leaders believed that control of these key areas of competence should be returned to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction with the single market, with business representatives saying that the costs of regulation from Brussels now outweigh the benefits of being in Europe's trading zone, even 40 percent of large enterprises, traditionally the most pro-European of all companies, agreed.
Last and most revealing, our survey of business leaders found that a clear majority want the UK to pursue a policy of amending the treaty and a relationship with the EU based on trade rather than politics.
This result, which has been seen among businesses of all sizes and the largest business groups, shows that businesses are pushing for a "meaningful change" that will bring powers back to the UK.
The stakes are high – achieving changes to the treaty and better terms for the UK would ensure a 16 per cent shift in the vote to remain in the EU.
The prime minister should have no doubt: this poll shows that British business supports his plan to renegotiate the terms of britain's membership in the EU.
It also shows that business expects the revision to lead to a significant shift in the current balance of power back towards the UK.
Better conditions for British business are possible and are becoming increasingly necessary as the eurozone embarks on a path of closer economic and financial unification.
Priority must be given to jobs and economic growth in the UK, and as our survey shows, for businesses this means an increased focus on trade and fundamental changes in Brussels' regulatory activities.
