Russia beyond the fight for pollution of cities by cars
Attempts to solve the transport problems of large cities have been observed in most megacities of the world since the second half of the twentieth century.
As a rule, it was either about their reconstruction and expansion of highways, or about attempts to reduce the demand for car trips, the number of cars and the time of their use.
The example of Singapore is widely known, where strict quotas for the growth of the number of private cars have been introduced, and the right to purchase them is bought at auctions.
Its price can be two to three times higher than the price of the car itself.
European cities, including London, have introduced a fee for entering the city center.
In Germany, for example, in Hamburg and Stuttgart, so-called green zones are being introduced, where only cars with a certain eco-class that also use high-quality fuels (including biofuels or electric cars) are allowed to enter.
Beijing's Environmental Protection Agency, for example, approved in 2012 a "five-year clean air plan" worth about 250 billion yuan (about $40 billion).
As Li Kunsheng, director of the transport pollution control department of the municipal environmental protection bureau of Beijing, told Kommersant, the main goal of the five-year plan is to reduce the leading air pollutants by 20-35% by 2017, increase the number of private cars to a level not exceeding 6 million (now 5.2 million), as well as increase fuel use per vehicle by no more than 5%.
According to the agency, now motor transport in Beijing is responsible for 22.5% of total air pollution.
Among the main measures of the program are the restriction of the use of road transport, as well as the introduction of additional taxes for car owners.
Among other things, urban measures of the "green five-year plan" include an accelerated transition to European fuel standards compared to the rest of the country, the introduction of a local system of eco-standards and labeling of cars and fuel, restrictions on the entry of cars into the central part of the city, a ban on the use of obsolete vehicles (in addition, the creation of incentive financial programs for the replacement of old cars with hybrid or electric vehicles), the development of electric transport (including  public and service), the development of public transport (including high-speed).
Beijing's automotive innovations also include a ban on all private cars from driving within the fifth ring road (there are six of them in the Capital of the People's Republic of China) one day a week (the relevant information is contained in the license plate of the vehicle), as well as the issuance of registration plates for cars based on the lottery (for example, in 2011, the first year of the lottery, the total number of permits for registration of private cars in Beijing was only a third of the number of  2010).
According to the current state program "Environmental Protection for 2012-2020", the number of cities with high and very high air pollution should be reduced to 128 (in 2012 there were 138).
According to the Ministry of Natural Resources, in 2011, "mobile sources" accounted for 41% of all pollutant emissions into the atmosphere of cities.
In Moscow, for example, emissions from cars are ten times higher than industrial, and in St. Petersburg - nine times.
In the Russian Federation, they are only beginning to think about the possibilities of restrictive regulation of cars on the streets of cities.
Mikhail Blinkin, Director of the HSE Institute of Transport Economics and Transport Policy, believes that administrative and fiscal measures aimed at suppressing the demand for road trips are obviously unpopular, they can be adopted by society only if they are completely universal.
In the case of Moscow, a unique problem arises related to the structure of its fleet, where there are two clusters of weakly sensitive to any regulatory influences - official and personal cars, as well as cars of "privileged" users, the total number of which is at least 200 thousand (about 5% of the total number of the Moscow fleet).
Recently, urbanists from the ECOM center in St. Petersburg prepared a study that analyzes the balance of urban areas between residential development, the area of the road surface and the number of vehicles.
The main conclusions of the researchers: the city center is provided with roads two times less than required, and most motorists living in the center do not use cars every day, leaving them for a long time in parking lots or just on the streets.
As a result, it is proposed to build not parking lots, but car storage, not to expand, but to reduce the roadway (so that the streets become more pedestrian-friendly), as well as to limit the use and placement of personal vehicles within the boundaries of the territory of the protection zone of the historical center (a total area of about 3212 hectares covering a number of central districts of the city).
A tax maneuver will lead to a rise in the price of fuel, which provides for an increase in the mineral extraction tax (MET) on oil simultaneously with a reduction in export duties and an increase in excise taxes.
According to experts, these measures can bring an additional 619.3 billion rubles to the budget.
Drive through mud, rivers and jungles for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free medical care in rural Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend seeing hundreds of patients.
In this West African country, there are not so many doctors – only one in 5,000 people.
