This man will receive $250,000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his father come back to life and again fall into unconsciousness, wandering around hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Djamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but the resulting infection spread to the brain and caused a hematoma that reminded of itself for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," Georges Bwelle said.
If we had the money, we would have taken him out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwelle accompanied his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals for years, receiving any treatment they could receive.
"It's not easy," Bwelle said.
You can leave the house at 5 a.m., run to the hospital to be the first, but you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some may die because they have to wait.
The situation hasn't changed much since Bwelle's father passed away in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, Cameroon has only one doctor per 5,000 people.
By comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 people.
And even if Cameroonians could see a doctor, many of them would not be able to afford it.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of its health spending is private.
"Their only problem is poverty," Bwelle said.
"And because of poverty, they can't enjoy their lives."
Seeing the suffering of his father and so many of his compatriots, Bwelle was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. Georges Bwellet and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries.
He himself became a doctor and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital of Yaoundé.
He also founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, which organizes trips to the countryside on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have assisted nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 other people are crammed into vans, tied to rooftops with medical supplies and drive across rough terrain to visit villages in need of help.
They are not always accompanied by luck.
More than once they had to push cars through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are greeted like true heroes: it's a celebration with songs and dances and the best facilities the locals can offer.
The free medical care in these villages is indeed a cause for celebration, and Bwelle, with his big smile and boundless energy, is more than happy to join in the fun.
The next morning, the team begins to receive hundreds of patients.
"We take 500 people on every trip," Bwelle said.
They come from all over the neighborhood within a 60 kilometer radius of the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides a variety of medical services.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates — documents needed for school that many poor families simply can't afford.
In the evenings, the team performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually carried out in the school building, municipality or in the house; After the procedure, patients get up and go to the recovery area to make room for the next person.
Using a generator to illuminate the operating room and sanitize the equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
It's an unsustainable pace, but the dedication of the brigade is usually helped by the village musicians.
"They beat drums all night to keep us awake and keep working," Bwelle said.
On Sunday, the crew members head back to town, tired but proud of their work.
This group, made up of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students, has performed 700 free surgeries over the past year, and they know that their help can make a huge difference to those they help.
One person explained that the free hernia surgery he received would allow him to work again.
"It will change the future for me and my family," the man said.
In addition to these clinical appointments on weekends and working in the hospital as a surgeon, Bwelle also works nights in private medical clinics around Yaoundé.
It is this second job, he said, that provides 60% of his nonprofit funding; the remaining funds are covered by private donations.
"I don't even know when he sleeps," said Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia who volunteered in Bwelle's group.
He's always either in the hospital or trying to make money for the organization so that these campaigns can continue.
For future doctors and nurses like O'Malley coming from the U.S. and Europe to join Bwell in carrying out his tasks, it's an opportunity to practice that they would never get at home.
"We were able to assist in surgeries where we helped remove blood stains or hold instruments for Dr. Bwelle," O'Malley said.
As a sophomore, you would never have gotten that opportunity in America.
Student volunteers usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon, often arriving with donated medicines.
But upon arrival in Yaoundé, their food, transport and tuition pays for Bwelle.
"He's a hero, no doubt," O'Malley said.
He gives his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwelle, the almost constant workload is not an ordeal.
To help others live a happy life, to fulfill the promise made to his father - this is what brings him great joy.
"I'm so happy when I do this work," Bwelle said.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do this to make people laugh, to reduce their pain.
Go to the ASCOVIME website and see how you can help.
