Goldman Sachs warned of risks for the Russian economy
Goldman Sachs has warned of growing risks to the main driver of Russia's fragile economic growth: consumption.
First of all, this is the crisis of non-payments on unsecured consumer loans and mass layoffs of workers.
Our main concern now is not that growth has slowed, but rather the structure of that growth.
Recently, it is completely due to consumption, which almost does not slow down, "said Clemens Grafe, chief economist at Goldman Sachs for Russia, presenting yesterday the quarterly report of the investment bank on the Russian economy.
Now the nominal growth of wages in Russia is about 10%.
With inflation of 6%, it will be able to provide future consumer demand at about the current level, Goldman Sachs expects.
But the profitability of Russian companies is falling, therefore, most likely, they will be engaged in optimizing personnel costs.
Today we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages grow by 10%, then GDP - only by 2%, - explained Mr. Grafe.
Companies faced a reduction in profitability.
If it does not grow, it can lead to layoffs and an increase in unemployment.
Russian business cannot not raise salaries, comments Vladimir Pantyushin, chief economist at Barclays Capital for Russia and the CIS.
Unemployment is near historic lows, competition for workers is high.
To lure employees from the outside or keep the current ones, employers have to raise salaries.
Consumption in Russia is also supported by a very rapid growth in consumer lending.
According to Mr. Grafe, due to extremely high rates on consumer loans, this type of lending does not have a multiplicative effect on the country's economy.
"We did not see any benefit for the economy from the growth of consumer lending, the money does not disperse throughout the economy, but returns to the same banks in the form of interest payments," the economist said.
But the problem is different - Goldman Sachs expects an increase in delinquencies on unsecured loans.
They are taken mainly by poor people who have nothing to provide as collateral.
Interest on such loans is high.
As a result, they are more often not returned," said Mr. Grafe.
Therefore, the second threat to economic growth in Russia is a possible crisis of non-payments on unsecured loans.
Vasily Solodkov, Director of the HSE Banking Institute, is already seeing signs of a brewing banking crisis.
Small credit organizations, not having access to cheap resources, which state-owned banks have, were forced to attract funds from the population at high interest rates.
In response, state-owned banks went on the warpath and began to reduce loan rates, the economist continues.
Small credit institutions cannot issue loans at the same interest rates, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If state-owned banks do not abandon dumping, Russia faces a full-fledged banking crisis, Vasily Solodkov believes.
The economist considers the deprivation of licenses of a number of banks in recent weeks a harbinger of a massive collapse.
"State-owned banks themselves will not cope with this situation: the deposit insurance system was not originally designed for a systemic crisis," the head of the institute warns.
But the growth of consumption will slow down even without a crisis of non-payments, the investment bank believes, due to the refusal to index the salaries of civil servants and the military, laid down in the current version of the draft budget.
Part of the blow to consumption will be mitigated by freezing the tariffs of natural monopolies (and, as a consequence, lower inflation).
But only partially: if investments do not grow (and there are no prerequisites for this yet - see the reference), consumption growth will still slow down, Goldman Sachs is sure.
Vladimir Pantyushin of Barclays Capital does not yet see the prerequisites for the implementation of pessimistic scenarios.
"The main risk is still the fall in the price of oil," he says.
According to him, the Russian economy will begin to decline with the cost of oil below $ 90 per barrel.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the Central Bank is not yet able to reduce interest rates in the economy.
There is a paradoxical picture: inflation has decreased, and banks have begun to raise rates.
This may mean that they did not believe the Central Bank, which announced the transition to inflation targeting," said Clemens Grafe.
The interest rate policy of the Central Bank does not affect market rates, it affects only interbank lending rates.
"For the Central Bank, this is the collapse of all hopes," Clemens Grafe said.
The money received at the auctions of the Central Bank, banks use not to lend to the economy, but to manage their liquidity
As soon as the rate is reduced, the exchange rate immediately changes, which means that the funds are trying to go to speculation against the ruble.
"Sooner or later, the Central Bank will understand that this strategy does not work," said Mr. Grafe and recalled that the state plans to let the ruble float "freely" by the end of 2015.
But it will be necessary either to do this earlier, or to raise the key rate of the Central Bank (5.5%), he said.
According to him, the ruble exchange rate is now artificially inflated by 10%.
The ruble has only one way - to weaken, - the expert concludes.
But if the Central Bank casts even a shadow of doubt in financiers that the elimination of the currency corridor is not part of the policy to weaken the ruble, it can bring down the ruble much more.
