FAA: "Air passengers can now use gadgets on airplanes (but not call from a mobile phone)"
Air passengers will be able to use their electronic devices throughout the flight to read, work, play games, watch movies and listen to music, but not talk on mobile phones, according to long-awaited new guidelines released Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration.
But passengers shouldn't expect the changes to happen immediately.
How quickly such a change is implemented will vary depending on the airline, FAA administrator Michael Wortha said at a news conference.
Airlines will have to show the FAA how their aircraft meet the new guidelines and that they are updating their flight crew training manuals and stowage rules to comply with the new guidelines.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices on aircraft.
Delta and JetBlue were among the airlines that had already submitted plans.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the expansion of the use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA said.
Currently, passengers are required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the plane door closes.
They shouldn't restart them until the plane has reached an altitude of 10,000 feet and the captain has given the go-ahead.
Passengers must turn off their devices again when the plane descends for landing, and do not turn them on until the plane is on the ground.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose planes are adequately protected from electronic interference could allow passengers to use these devices during takeoff, landing and taxiing, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft modified so that passengers can use Wi-Fi at high altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional Flight Attendants, welcomed the changes.
"Once the new policy is safely implemented (and we are going to work closely with the carrier to achieve this), it will be a win-win," Glading said.
We are frankly tired of feeling "on duty at school" when it comes to this issue.
But internet connections for surfing, exchanging emails, texting or downloading data would still be banned at less than 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will be asked to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to airplane mode.
Thus, there is still no "Words with Friends" – an intelligent Internet game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011, when a sensational incident occurred: the actor was removed from an American Airlines plane for refusing to turn off the device while the plane was at the landing gate.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, will still need to be stowed in the luggage compartment, as they can injure someone if they fly throughout the cabin.
Calls from a mobile phone in flight will also continue to be prohibited.
Regulatory authority over phone calls is vested in the Federal Communications Commission, not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices during takeoff and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert at CBS News, said cell phones are still considered a risk.
"Cell phones are really a problem, not just because they could potentially interfere with navigation devices, but we know from the FCC that they can interfere with cell towers when an airplane is in the air," Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to look into the issue recommended last month that the government allow greater use of personal electronic devices.
Pressure has been mounting on the FAA in recent years to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics, such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri, argue that there are no good security reasons for the bans.
Compliance with restrictions is also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies show that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore instructions to turn off their devices.
The FAA began restricting passengers' use of electronic devices in 1966 in response to reports of interference with navigation and communication equipment when passengers began carrying FM radios, the high-tech gadgets of the time.
New airliners are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also being developed and approved by the FAA as resistant to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers the use of Wi-Fi at cruising altitude for several years.
Aircraft modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of liners are geared toward the wider use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices typically emit radio signals of much lower power than previous generations of devices.
E-book readers, for example, emit only minimal signals when turning pages.
But signals become more powerful when devices load or send data.
Among those who sought to ease restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers was the company Amazon.com.
In 2011, the company loaded an entire airliner with its Kindle e-book readers and flew it to check for problems, but never found them.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about whether the use of the devices poses any risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Air Passengers said he believes interference from devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members said there are only isolated pilot reports confirming that the devices can interfere with aircraft systems, and most of those reports are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to require passengers to turn off devices during instrument landings in reduced visibility.
A group of representatives of the tourism industry welcomed these changes, calling them a sensible step towards passengers, who now use a variety of technological devices.
