Frontier Airlines will charge for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge passengers up to $100 for carrying hand luggage on board their flight.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for carry-on luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, though their announcement on Wednesday said passengers would be able to keep the entire can.
The new hand luggage fee applies to bags in the upper luggage compartments, so small bags placed under the seat will remain free.
Frontier said it will charge $25 if the fee is paid in advance, and $100 if travelers pay only when they are at the gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 fee should force passengers to take care of paying in advance.
"We don't want to charge for it," she said.
Airlines began charging for the first and second bags checked in in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these fees stuff as much as they can into hand luggage placed in the upper luggage compartments, which is why there is often not enough space in these compartments.
Fees are one way to get passengers to carry less on board.
O'Malley said this new levy isn't really for making money.
The fact is that the most loyal customers of Frontier claim that finding a place in the upper luggage compartments is becoming increasingly difficult.
Passengers who buy tickets on the airline's website will not have to pay.
This means that one passenger in the queue at the frontier flight exit can get the opportunity to carry a bag for free, while the next passenger in the queue can pay $ 100 for the same bag.
O'Malley said the change in procedures on frontier's website and at check-in counters is designed to ensure passengers are aware of the fee before they reach the boarding gate.
Frontier's new hand luggage fee won't start charging until the summer, though a date hasn't been set yet.
Passengers often complain about luggage fees and other fees, but airlines adore them.
They argue that handling luggage costs money, and passengers who need the service have to pay for it.
Many on Wall Street see the addition of baggage fees as a sign that airlines are charging enough money to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
However, most of them did not concern fees for hand luggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. introduced the first hand luggage levy three years ago, and another discounter, Allegiant Air, later followed suit.
The only other airline with such a levy is Hungary's Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the surcharges.
He estimated in a December 2011 report that the levy on hand luggage brings Spirit $50 million a year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines executive, recently flew on a Spirit flight, and he was wondering what he would find at the gate when passengers faced Spirit's unusual hand luggage fee.
"The landing process was the smoothest I've seen in my airline career," he said.
I expected to see gnashing of teeth and a fight at the gate.
The plane was full, he said, "and the landing was swift."
Frontier also follows Spirit for a $2 fee for coffee, tea, soda or juice.
Frontier said passengers who receive soda or juice can keep the entire can and that topping up the coffee will be provided free of charge.
It will continue to distribute water for free.
US Airways briefly tried to charge for drinks in 2008, but abandoned it seven months later, after passengers began complaining and no other major airline followed suit.
Frontier's initiative to charge for hand luggage when passengers do not buy tickets directly from the airline is its latest measure to attract customers to its website.
Airlines pay online ticket sellers such as Orbitz between $10 and $25 for each ticket sold.
This gave all airlines an incentive to encourage passengers to buy tickets directly from them, rather than contacting an online travel agency.
However, Frontier has gone furthest in this area.
In September, it began giving half as many frequent flyer bonus miles to customers who bought tickets through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, she cut the premium number of miles to 25 percent of the trip's miles.
So, a trip of 1,000 miles with Frontier, purchased from an online travel agency, would allow you to get 250 miles.
In addition, passengers can only choose a seat in advance if they buy tickets directly from the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base in her hometown of Denver, but its business is shrinking and becoming unprofitable.
Revenue was down 9 percent and flying capabilities were down nearly 13 percent in the first quarter, according to financial results released Wednesday by parent company Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic is trying to improve Frontier's finances through the sale of the airline.
