"Germany must wake up," says Oliver Grün, president of BITMi, which represents Germany's small and medium-sized IT companies.
German companies are convinced that the U.S. now poses almost the same risk as China in the areas of industrial espionage and data theft, according to a study published in July by the consulting agency EY.
In all the documents disclosed by Mr. Snowden, however, there has been no evidence so far that the U.S. has transferred trade secrets of foreign companies to its own companies.
Politicians expressed concern that the EU lacks certain capabilities in the field of information technology and the Internet, and expressed the opinion that it should try to reduce its dependence on the United States.
Businessmen are skeptical about this.
Someone in the German parliament says we should create a German Google.
I can only close my eyes and slowly open them again...
"It's not an option," says Gasso Plattner, president of German business software company SAP.
If there is a need for a powerful European IT industry, it should not have been allowed to die more than 20 years ago.
Everything is subsidized in Germany, from coal to cars to farmers.
Everything except the IT industry.
Yet the reach and technical sophistication of U.S. spying agencies, made famous by The Snowden revelations, came as a shock to some companies that previously thought China posed the biggest surveillance risk.
A big shift is taking place in cloud technology, where European ceos have become more aware that data stored in the U.S. is in the same jurisdiction and therefore potentially vulnerable.
According to a study conducted by the trade association Cloud Security Alliance, about 10 percent of its non-US participants abandoned plans to use the services of a US-based cloud provider after the exposure of the American program for data mining Prism.
Jim Sneijb, one of SAP's chief executives, said: "We see consumers asking a new question that didn't arise a year ago, namely where is my data stored and can you guarantee that it will physically remain in this jurisdiction."
Many German leaders argue that the latest reports are just confirmation of what they already knew: powerful states want to steal their most valuable secrets, and therefore this data must be protected at all costs.
That economic espionage is taking place is not surprising.
It always happened.
"This has been the subject of discussion for many years and has not changed significantly in the current controversy," says Kurt Bock, chief executive officer of chemical company BASF.
Americans spy on us at the commercial and industrial level, and we spy on them too, because it is in our national interest to protect our commercial enterprises.
Corporate leaders usually do not like to brag about the retaliatory measures they have taken, as this can provide an advantage to the enemy.
In large companies, the idea has long been internalized that taking a free flash drive at an exhibition or leaving a laptop unattended in a hotel room is, to say the least, imprudent.
Ulrich Hackenberg, a member of the board of directors of the automaker Audi, says that for many years it has been standard practice to collect mobile phones before board meetings so that they cannot be used as listening devices.
Germany's Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution recommends company executives to consider using simple prepaid mobile phones when traveling abroad due to the vulnerability of smartphones.
Prepaid mobile phones are subsequently discarded.
However, there are concerns that small and medium-sized companies remain vulnerable to hacking and surveillance.
In Germany, many such companies are leaders in the global market in their specific niche.
"Small and medium-sized companies often lack the experience, staff and financial resources to effectively protect corporate secrets from unauthorized access," the BfV report warns.
The U.S. is warning its own companies about economic espionage by other countries.
The U.S. National Intelligence Report in February placed France, along with Russia and Israel, in the second row of violators who engage in hacking for economic intelligence, after China, according to The Washington Post.
A member of the board of directors of the prestigious German company confirmed that when it comes to economic espionage, "the French are the worst of all."
Bernard Scarsini, the former head of France's domestic intelligence agency DCRI, reportedly said in an interview this month: "The services are well aware that all countries, even when they cooperate in the fight against terrorism, spy on their allies."
