The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has released guidelines for schools regarding allergies in children
On Wednesday, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention released a list of guidelines for controlling food allergies in children in schools.
This is the first list of such recommendations that the US government has issued, while the number of school-age children suffering from food allergies is growing.
One in 20 children in the U.S. now have a food allergy.
The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention found that the prevalence of food allergies among children increased by 18 percent from 1997 to 2007.
The guide provides information for schools on how to raise awareness among teachers and staff about food allergies in children and how to provide assistance in the event of an allergic reaction.
It also recommends that schools keep supplies of epinephrine — the EpiPen automatic medical syringe is most commonly used for injections — to assist with potentially fatal anaphylaxis.
State legislatures recently made changes to regulations to allow schools to make adrenaline rushes with less difficulty.
The notice also contains a list of typical symptoms described by children who have an allergic reaction.
Children may say, "It feels like something is poking my tongue," "it feels like I have hair on my tongue," or "my tongue is pinching."
