U.S. cuts food allowance for poor
Food allowance for a family of four is reduced by $ 36 per month
Since Friday, the financial support of food stamps, known as "food stamps", has been reduced in the United States, as the corresponding state program expires.
A family of four will now be allocated $36 a month less for food allowance than before, officials say.
This will affect 47 million of the poorest Americans.
According to Reuters, in fiscal year 2012, the allowance per person averaged $133 a month.
Spending on food aid in the U.S. rose to $80 billion a year due to rising unemployment and food prices.
Roughly 14 percent of Americans rely on free food aid for "food stamps," which have been dubbed since the old days, when they took the form of paper coupons.
When the current economic crisis hit, the program was expanded to boost growth and help the poorest Americans.
But Republicans in Congress are demanding further cuts to the program, saying it should be aimed at helping those who need it most.
Grocery store owners across America worry that the cuts will lead to lower consumer spending.
U.S. congressmen continue to debate how to cut funding for the government even further.
Because of the new rules introduced by the Russian customs, hundreds of trucks have been standing in line at the border with Russia for almost a week.
Today, Donetsk officials promised to provide drivers with drinking water and install composting toilets.
Hundreds of trucks have accumulated at border points at the entrance to Russia.
This situation arose due to a change in the rules of customs clearance of goods.
Ukrainian border guards and customs officers confirm: the queue is created by the Russian side, which did not warn in advance about the innovations.
Since October 28, the customs authorities of Russia have begun to apply additional measures to guarantee the delivery of goods, - said Vladimir Denisov, Deputy Head of the Eastern Customs.
The document of the new sample is applied in countries that have acceded to the convention on international transport.
Checkpoints are working in an enhanced mode.
The correspondent of "FACTS" visited the border and talked with truckers who were hostages of the situation.
Prices in the roadside shop-cafe at the checkpoint "Novoazovsk" are growing every day, as well as the queue of trucks.
Trucks stand in several rows, stretching for about two kilometers.
Customs terminal Novoazovsk - Veselo-Voznesenka provides one of the most important transport routes from the south of Ukraine along the international highway.
From here, cargoes are sent to the Stavropol Territory of Russia, Kazakhstan, Georgia, Armenia.
On Sunday, they were still allowed to go until midnight, and then these rules were introduced, - complains trucker Alexei Golovanev (pictured), who carries cargo from Turkey to Kazakhstan in transit through Russia and has been sleeping in his car for almost a week.
According to the new rules, in order to cross the border, I need an additional package of documents and payment for cargo insurance.
The amount depends on the value of the cargo and the distance to which it is transported.
Minimum insurance - 4.5-5 thousand rubles (about 1100-1300 hryvnia).
Those who travel nearby (say, to Georgia, Armenia) with a cargo worth up to 50 thousand dollars, pay about 15 thousand rubles (3800 hryvnia) and pass.
And the rest are stuck - because no one has such a lot of money with them!
Imagine, if the driver carries a cargo worth only four thousand dollars, but already to Moscow, he needs 90 thousand rubles (almost 23 thousand hryvnias) to pay for transit!
There are no conditions for survival at the border, - complain truckers who have settled down near their cars.
In border shops and cafes it is always expensive, but we have not met such prices as here!
Sellers orientated themselves and quickly inflated them: 15 hryvnia is a loaf, seven hryvnias - a cup of coffee, 25 hryvnia - a bowl of soup.
And there is only one café.
And there is no toilet.
In the steppe we sleep, there we go to the toilet.
No washing, no shaving...
I can not get out of the car for a week, my wife has prepared everything for me on the road.
I will last a week, - another trucker Viktor Skotarenko consoles himself.
But will it be my car's turn in a week?
How much do you have one and a half liters of water? - We are interested in the only border shop.
There are 11 and 15 hryvnias.
Is it a crystal bottle or is the water infused with silver?
We have a café, not a shop.
Take it while there is something else, the saleswoman retorts.
After the situation began to be covered in the media, the authorities of the region drew attention to the plight of Ukrainian drivers.
The leadership of the Amvrosievskaya and Novoazovskaya district state administrations were instructed to provide everyone who is idle in line at the Ukrainian-Russian border with drinking water, - said the acting chairman of the Donetsk regional state administration Sergey Dergunov.
Ambulance crews are now on duty at checkpoints.
Also, for the convenience of people, composting toilets will be installed.
According to the official, the problem associated with queues will be solved in the coming days.
According to the press service of the Donetsk Regional State Administration, as of October 31, 32 and 68 cars were idle at the international checkpoints "Uspenka" and "Novoazovsk", respectively.
"FACTS" will monitor the development of the situation.
Sony expects a lower annual profit
Japanese electronics manufacturer Sony Corporation, ending the past quarter with a net loss of 19.3 billion yen, or $ 197 million, reduced its profit forecast for the current fiscal year.
Sony's results for the period from July to September 2013 were more depressing than expected, which is due to a drop in demand for televisions, video cameras and personal computers manufactured by the Japanese corporation.
Sony's television business, which in the second quarter brought the company its first operating profit in three years in the amount of 5.2 billion yen, in the reporting period fell again to 9.3 billion yen of operating loss.
The Japanese consumer electronics market is going through hard times, especially due to declining demand for TVs.
And while competitors are looking for a way out of a difficult situation, Sony continues to focus on the consumer segment.
For example, one of Sony's main rivals, Panasonic Corporation, has recently shifted its focus to industrial components: here the company's sales are growing rapidly, especially due to automotive systems and environmentally friendly technologies.
As a result, by the end of the fiscal year, which will end in March 2014, Sony expects to receive 179 billion yen of operating profit against the previously expected 230 billion yen.
At the same time, according to Thomson Reuters, analysts assumed that this figure would be much higher and amount to 221 billion yen.
In an effort to get out of the crisis, Sony is expanding its product line.
In the middle of this month, the start of sales of "smart" watches from the Japanese corporation was announced, endowed with a number of fashionable functions that will get rid of the need to take out a smartphone from your pocket 100 times a day.
After Sony lowered its full-year forecast for profit and revenue, the company's shares in the morning at the opening of torogs in Tokyo lost more than 11%, falling to the level of 1668 yen per share.
