In addition, according to Mikheev, there are much more patriotic people in Russia than religious ones, but at the same time the law punishes insulting the feelings of believers, and it is possible to insult patriotic feelings with almost impunity.
According to the people's representative, it is necessary to equate the insult of patriotic feelings with extremist activity and prescribe an appropriate punishment in the 282nd article of the Criminal Code.
The bill provides for punishment for insulting patriotic feelings: from a 100,000-ruble fine to a 5-year imprisonment.
In the new composition of public monitoring commissions, the influence of jailers will increase
Today, the Council of the Public Chamber (OP) can approve new compositions of public supervisory commissions (PMC) in 43 regions of Russia.
If the option put to the vote is adopted, the lobbyists of the security forces will increase their influence.
PMCs are public structures that monitor the conditions of detention in places of deprivation of liberty.
The cases of Sergei Magnitsky and Leonid Razvozzhaev, the unrest in the Kopeysk colony - it is through the PMC that most of the resonant incidents behind bars get publicity.
For control over the PMC there is a struggle between human rights activists and lobbyists of the security forces.
At the meeting of the op working group on the formation of the PMC, I proposed to make the experience of human rights activities the selection criterion.
"It was not accepted, and the lists were formed without developing criteria," says Valery Borshchev.
Borshchev is the current chairman of the Moscow Monitoring Commission and the Association of Independent Observers, an all-Russian structure of human rights defenders dealing with prison issues.
When he was a State Duma deputy from Yabloko, he developed a law regulating the activities of the PMC.
The Council of the Civic Chamber should vote for the composition of the PMC in 43 regions of the country.
Less than a thousand applicants apply for 1800 vacant places, and in Ingushetia and Kabardino-Balkaria competitions could not be organized due to the lack of candidates.
The OP promises to organize additional recruitment for vacant seats.
The PMC of Moscow is one of the few commissions with a competition, despite the fact that in the new composition instead of 20 there will be 40 participants.
According to Borshchev, in the current composition of the capital's commission there are 11 human rights defenders and 9 law enforcers, and in the version that is on the vote in the OP, the ratio changes to 17 to 23.
At the same time, 30 human rights defenders wanted to get into the capital's commission.
But the representative of the "Combat Brotherhood" Vyacheslav Kalinin can re-enter the new composition.
He was a member of the PMC for three years, but never visited prisoners.
Borshchev believes that the security forces, by appointing their chairman of the PMC, will be able to make the work of human rights defenders unbearable, so human rights defenders do not exclude a collective withdrawal from the commission.
In their opinion, the promotion of the security forces is coordinated by a member of the PMC Anton Tsvetkov, who heads the "Officers of Russia" - an organization that defends the interests of law enforcement agencies.
"I do not eat babies for breakfast," Anton Tsvetkov told RBC daily.
He denies lobbying for the promotion of any lists and says he has no intention of preventing human rights defenders from visiting arrested opposition figures.
According to Tsvetkov, he was not even interested in which list is now being voted for in the OP.
He considers Borshchev's disclosure of information a form of pressure.
