Earlier tonight, online server monitoring systems registered that the NSA site had been down for at least six hours, and the site was still unavailable to some users.
Earlier, an NSA spokesperson told ABC News that the agency's internal secret network was "by no means" hacked.
No classified information is in danger, the spokesman said.
At least one online group of activist hackers said it was responsible for disabling the NSA website with a DDoS attack.
DDoS attacks are designed to overwhelm the target site with traffic until the servers are overwhelmed and the site goes down.
Hacker tactics are relatively simple, and attacks are not designed to infiltrate the target system's internal network.
The previously super-secret NSA, once dubbed "No Such Agency," has been the focus of public attention and fierce criticism in recent months after a string of revelations about its extensive surveillance programs abroad and at home — all a reaction to secret NSA files stolen from the agency and published by a frustrated former NSA employee Edward Snowden.
The growing controversy around the agency has sparked speculation that today's incident was the result of targeted actions by hackers.
