The agency "Rosbalt" was deprived of the status of the media for obscene language
On October 31, the Moscow City Court decided to invalidate the license on the registration of the Rosbalt agency, Lenta writes.
Roskomnadzor insisted on depriving the agency of its media status for systematic and gross violations of the law on the media.
During the trial, an unpleasant precedent was created: the court considered it possible to close the media, actually denying the publication the right to put forward counter-arguments.
What is "Rosbalt"
CJSC "Rosbalt Information Agency" was established in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In the following years, the agency opened a second head office in Moscow and a number of regional divisions.
The agency also has representative offices in the countries of the former USSR.
Since 2001, Rosbalt has developed and functioned as a federal information and analytical agency.
By the mid-2000s, the agency was on the list of the most recognizable private Internet media in Russia.
At the same time, Rosbalt has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of the agency's exclusive publications was (and still is) notes with reference to sources in law enforcement agencies.
Talks about the proximity of the publication to law enforcement agencies continued throughout the existence of the agency.
Along with the fact that Rosbalt had an extensive database of sources in various departments, the fact that Natalia Chaplina, the wife of Viktor Cherkesov, was at the head of the project, also spoke in favor of such assumptions.
At the same time, Chaplina's role in the leadership of Rosbalt is not completely clear: most often she is called the "project manager".
The general director of the agency is Larisa Afonina, the editor-in-chief is Nikolay Ulyanov.
Recently, Rosbalt has not appeared in the ratings of federal media - neither in terms of citations nor in terms of audience.
In October, the agency took 25th place in the ranking of attendance at Russian media sites according to LiveInternet.
According to the same LiveInternet, the average daily audience of the rosbalt.ru site is about 150 thousand unique visitors (and up to 500 thousand views), monthly - about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials over the past five months are notes about the Helplessness of the Kremlin in relations with Ukraine, the death of the soloist of the group "King and Jester", pogroms in the capital's Biryulev.
Rosbalt's conflict with Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when amendments to the law on the media came into force, prohibiting journalists from swearing.
The agency found forbidden language in two videos published on the agency's website ("Dzhigit from Krasnodar" and "Pussy Riot desecrated oil rigs").
Further sides are described in different ways.
Roskomnadzor, on the basis of the discovered video materials, accused Rosbalt of gross and systematic violation of the law on the media and appealed to the court with a demand to take away the agency's license.
Rosbalt stated that the department's claims were unlawful: firstly, the videos were not editorial materials, secondly, swear words in them were disguised, and, thirdly, immediately after the warning, the videos were removed from the site.
Representatives of the agency appealed the claims of Roskomnadzor in the magistrate's court - and when on October 22, 2013, the Moscow City Court accepted the claim of Roskomnadzor, the consideration of these complaints was still ongoing.
However, already on the 25th, the magistrate judge ruled not in favor of Rosbalt: the editor-in-chief Nikolai Ulyanov was found guilty of violating the Code of Administrative Offenses and fined 20 thousand rubles - 10 thousand for each video.
Obviously, this predetermined the outcome of the hearing in the Moscow City Court - if you abandon the idea that the outcome could have been predetermined even earlier.
On October 31, the court decided to invalidate rosbalt's registration certificate, effectively depriving the agency of media status.
It cannot be said that Rosbalt remained alone during this confrontation.
The agency was supported by State Duma deputies (a statement addressed to the head of Roskomnadzor Alexander Zharov on October 10 was signed by 26 deputies; the document itself was submitted at the initiative of the Communist Party of the Russian Federation).
The illegality of the closure of the publication was stated by the head of the Union of Journalists of Russia Vsevolod Bogdanov, the chairman of the Moscow Union of Journalists Pavel Gusev and the head of the Presidential Council for Human Rights Mikhail Fedotov.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, the leadership of Roskomnadzor even provided him with some guarantees that it would not come to revoking the license.
The trial of Rosbalt showed that under whose jurisdiction it is safer for the media to be in Russia today is a big question.
The speech gene turned out to be a stimulator of synapse formation
Scientists from Johns Hopkins University and Mount Sinai School of Medicine have discovered a protein thanks to which the "speech gene" Foxp2 performs its function, stimulating the formation of new connections between neurons.
The study is published in Science, on the journal's website you can read its summary.
The Foxp2 gene is the first known gene whose function is directly related to speech.
It was possible to establish his role in 2001 thanks to the discovery of a family of several people who could not pronounce words correctly and sometimes did not even understand each other themselves.
Scientists have found that family members were impaired in the work of the Foxp2 gene, but how it performs its function remained unknown.
In a new study, biologists have shown that foxp2 performs at least part of its functions as a stimulator of the formation of new synapses in the area of the brain associated with the formation of speech.
He does this thanks to another gene, SRPX2.
The latter was discovered as a result of the search for factors that stimulate the formation of synapses.
SRPX2 turned out to be one of 10 similar genes found by the authors, with Foxp2 only on its activity.
The fact that SRPX2 really affects vocalization, scientists confirmed in an experiment on mice.
When the animals' gene activity was artificially reduced, they screamed less when separated from their mother.
If the activity of the gene was restored, the frequency of the sounds produced was also restored.
Previously, mice also showed a connection with the vocalization of Foxp2 itself.
Animals that were injected with a human copy of the gene squeaked more actively and at a lower frequency than normal mice.
Until now, however, scientists do not know whether the work of Foxp2 and, accordingly, the SRPX2 controlled by it is associated with purely "mechanical" properties of sound formation or more subtle processes.
