GM recalls a number of new pickups in the US to refine seat backs
General Motors Co is recalling nearly 19,000 brand-new 2014 Chevrolet Silverado and GMC Sierra pickups to address issues with manual seat backrest adjustment, according to Friday's notice from U.S. auto safety regulators.
On some of the pickups, the front seats may have a defect in the mechanism of inclination of the backrests.
As a result, the seat backs do not meet federal vehicle safety standards for head restraints.
"When a vehicle is struck from behind, the head restraint may not properly protect the driver and passengers, increasing the risk of injury," the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said in a notice posted on its website.
The recalled models were made between August 1 and September 10.
Production of GM pickups began in June and represents the most important launch of the car into mass production for the leading American automaker since its restructuring due to bankruptcy in 2009.
GM informed pickup truck owners of the defect in the first half of October.
The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration could not consider notifying owners due to the 16-day shutdown of the government, which lowered auto sales growth in October.
Sales of the Silverado and Sierra pickups, which have been upgraded for the 2014 lineup, rose about 20 percent during the first 10 months of this year, GM said Friday.
In October, GM sold 42,660 Silverado pickups and 16,503 Sierra pickups.
GM shares on the New York Stock Exchange rose 1.4 percent to $37.47 on Friday afternoon.
