George Kerevan: Breaking with Europe gives Scots a choice
Another day, another horror story about independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland will have to join the Pan-European Free Movement Area as a condition of EU membership.
It is the turn of stories about passport control in Bervik and the barbed wire border along Adrian's Wall.
True, the Strathclyde newspaper pointed to the possible economic benefits of freer movement in the rest of Europe, although – predictably – it did not make headlines.
Nor has anyone pointed out that EU member states spend a lot of time turning their formal rules in a way that suits them.
Since Scotland is not now part of the Schengen Area, continued non-compliance would be a cheap concession for Brussels to replace what it really wanted from the Scots.
So it's not a noteworthy story.
And so old that it has turned into a fossil: I first heard the "duck" that "independence means passport control" at least 40 years ago.
And yet there is an interesting point lost in the retelling of an old tale.
Why should an independent Scotland follow the orders of Europe at all?
Why swap London's yoke for brussels' yoke, especially now?
Here's the real European news: The great postwar plan to unite Europe has finally stalled.
With the euro crisis, the "Europe" project is officially dead.
Across the European Union, parties opposed to the EU or to abolish the euro as a single currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party – founded only this year – came out of nowhere and won nearly five million votes in September's federal elections, effectively displacing the Free Democrats (the equivalent of our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been internal opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
Nevertheless, the current economic crisis has become a turning point.
The austerity measures imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, and the shackles imposed on national economies through the preservation of the single currency, have led many people to believe that the "Europe" project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments operating with excessive budget deficits – this was only true for Greece.
In fact, the Eurosystem has locked its members in exchange rates favorable to German exporters , which German politicians want to preserve.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, southern Europe is at a pre-disadvantage in terms of production capabilities compared to Germany.
The only saving grace is to cut salaries and government spending, which is actively supported by Berlin.
Behind the current budget and currency problems is a deeper problem of Europe's productive capacity.
As a result of a set of green energy measures introduced by Brussels – a cipher meaning subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas than in the United States.
These are paralyzingly unfavorable price conditions, as we have seen in Grangemouth.
No amount of global wage freezes will stop the crushing victory of cheap U.S. shale gas over the European petrochemical industry.
As a result, a revolt is brewing, especially in France, once the EU's most ardent supporter.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on a par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a means of gaining political legitimacy, and has already imposed its own economic policies on Europe, leaving France's shattered economy in distress.
The result is marine Le Pen's right-wing, anti-EU National Front party that has just won a decisive by-election, dropping the ruling Socialist party to third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning to British Labour that it cannot be assumed that a split on the right would automatically affect the left.
What is Le Pen doing with his newfound popularity among the French white working class?
She wants to use next year's EU elections to create a bloc in the European Parliament against the EU and against the single currency.
If – and this is very likely – anti-EU parties gain support in these elections, such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament for the first time.
Here's my opinion: soon the growing sentiment against the EU and against the single currency in Europe will merge to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will once again become something of a vague "Europe of (sovereign) nations" that General de Gaulle liked.
Germany and a few dependent economies may retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will recover their own currencies.
My guess is that the UK is distancing itself from this project, hoping to get closer to the US.
Nevertheless, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific Ocean indicates the likelihood that the UK will be left unattended in the cold Atlantic.
Where does this leave Scotland?
We can choose to become a region of (essentially) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which means, among other things, sending Berlin and Brussels to hell.
I suspect scotland will be able to succeed under a freer European arrangement, provided we keep our currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries will be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider replicating Norway's experience and preserving our economic independence.
The Scottish National Party government in Scotland is – ironically – the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, winning a landslide majority in 2011 thanks to objections to spending cuts proposed (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor of the Exchequer Alistair Darling and the subsequent Coalition of the Tories and Liberal Democrats.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland now to vote for independence just to adopt the austerity measures imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
