Early puberty: aging earlier
African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white peers, research shows.
Physical changes do not mean that puberty is close.
No Evidence That Hormones or Other Chemicals Are To Blame
Experts believe that the obesity epidemic may be one of the triggers of early puberty
The tendency towards early puberty is not as pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in children's health and family issues.
Should a mother be frightened if her daughter begins to form the rudiments of the mammary gland and grow pubic hair at the age of 7 or 8?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplovitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent the new normal.
"I spend a lot of time reassuring parents — that doesn't usually mean the rapid onset of full puberty," Kaplovitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and axillary hair, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight shift in the age of menarche (first menstruation) over the past four decades.
In the United States, the median age is 12.5 years, down from 12.75 in 1970.
"Once breasts begin to develop, it takes at least two to three years before menarche," said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of Early Puberty in Girls: How to Deal with This Common Problem.
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty will progress.
There is debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but is considered "premature" when breast augmentation is accompanied by a sharp increase in growth before age 8.
In most cases, the process will slow down or stop – this is something that the pediatrician can monitor closely.
Faster progression can serve as a basis for tests with an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems, such as tumors or cysts.
There are procedures to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature aging of bones, which can eventually lead to stunted growth and low growth in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug or hormone therapy are based on the child's age, level of development, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplovitz is cautious about medications, but admits that "suppressing puberty can alleviate behavioral problems and girls' feelings that they are different from their peers."
The other big problem is understandable: parents just don't want their very young daughters to menstruate.
"They worry about the risk of pregnancy or even how they'll deal with hygiene issues," Kaplovitz said.
"It was a shock," recalls one woman whose daughter began menstruating at 10.
Although there were signs and we talked about menstruation, she wasn't emotionally ready.
She came home from school scared and upset that she was the first among her friends.
There are many publicized theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no consistent evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
In boys – as in girls – puberty occurs earlier.
Kaplovitz argues that the premise that carries the most weight is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study of girls between 6 and 9 years of age that links the amount of body fat to the timing of puberty.
Other evidence supports this finding, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Latino girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white peers.
There are various explanations.
Around the world, early puberty appears to be influenced by everything from economic conditions and climate to genes.
Another mystery: although boys have facial and pubic hair at a younger age, the tendency to complete early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other physicians participating in the AAP conference confirmed the complexity of this topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair occurs even in infants and toddlers.
"We have to be careful about how we determine the true onset of puberty," said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Gorieb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to receive instructions from a pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
"This could mean an earlier-than-expected conversation," Kaplovitz explained.
If you remain calm, your child will usually react well.
Girls who blossom early need confirmation that even when it happens early, the process is a normal part of life.
