RBS suspends two currency traders
The Royal Bank of Scotland has suspended two traders in its foreign exchange division, according to two people familiar with the situation, further confirming that global regulatory scrutiny of alleged manipulation of the foreign exchange market is rapidly gaining momentum.
Some of the world's biggest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, have confirmed that they are cooperating with regulators in investigations related to the world's largest financial market, which has a daily turnover of $5.3 trillion.
The two traders will be the first RBS employees to be suspended in the unfolding investigation, which echoes the scandal surrounding the manipulation of the LIBOR interbank rate.
Declining to comment on the suspensions, the bank confirmed that it had received requests for information from regulators this month.
"Our ongoing investigation into this matter is ongoing and we are fully cooperating with the FCA and our other regulators," the bank said two weeks ago.
Last month, people familiar with the matter said RBS had handed over email and instant messaging records that his former trader had received and sent to the UK's regulator, the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA).
This trader, Richard Usher, retired from RBS in 2010 and is known to have been granted a leave of absence in his current position as head of European spot currency trading at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, head of European spot trading at Citi, went on vacation this week, while Matt Gardiner, a former senior currency trader at Barclays and UBS, was suspended as Standard Chartered this week.
None of these traders have been charged with any wrongdoing.
Mr Usher's instant messaging contact group included bankers from Barclays and Citigroup, according to those with knowledge.
UBS said this week it had taken action against some of its employees after Swiss regulator Finma said it was investigating alleged manipulation of the foreign exchange market at a number of Swiss banks.
At least six regulators around the world — the European Commission, Finma, Switzerland's antitrust authority Weko, the FCA, the U.S. Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority — are looking into allegations that bankers colluded to influence the foreign exchange market.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse have also launched internal reviews or received requests for information from regulators, those familiar with the matter said.
Banks have been looking at instant messages and emails for years in search of cases of wrongdoing.
News of the inspections has roiled traders in what has been one of the largest sources of revenue for investment bank trading units in recent years, but has faced difficulties this year as low currency volatility reduces opportunities for resellers.
Some bankers have tried to downplay the gravity of the situation by saying that a vast and highly liquid currency market is nearly impossible to manipulate, but senior traders say this is not always true.
According to the senior trader, despite the huge volume of daily trading in the foreign exchange market, the fragmentation of liquidity between different trading platforms and the increased use by banks of their internal platforms means that "you can start to influence the market for a very small price."
The news came on the same day that Credit Suisse announced that it had fired one of the traders in its stock trading department on the London Stock Exchange this week after he caused a loss of nearly $6 million late last year.
The Bank has immediately notified the relevant authorities and is cooperating with its regulators.
"We are confident that the trader acted alone and that this issue was contained," Credit Suisse said.
