John Kerry says in his unprecedented admission that U.S. espionage has "gone unduely far."
John Kerry has demonstrated a softening of the tactics of protecting U.S. surveillance programs, making an unprecedented admission that in some cases U.S. espionage has "gone unduely far."
The secretary of state also admitted that he was guilty, along with Barack Obama, of being "on autopilot" during the appearance of Edward Snowden's high-profile revelations about NSA espionage activities.
These leaks have put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic row with its allies.
Speaking via video link at an open government conference in London, Mr Kerry said: "There is no doubt that the president and I, as well as other members of the government, actually took some of the things happening on autopilot, because such a possibility already existed – both during the Second World War, and in the very difficult years of the Cold War, and, of course, on September 11."
He then became the first senior member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had gone too far, but stressed that no one's rights had been violated.
He said: "In some cases it has gone too far.
And the president is determined to shed light on this issue and explain himself to the people, and is now conducting a thorough analysis so that no one has a sense of abuse.
I assure you, there is no abuse of innocent people in this process."
Mr. Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA had acted with good intentions and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: "We are working in a new world where people are willing to blow themselves up.
There is radical extremism in the world, reckless and determined to kill people, blow people up and attack governments.
And if you were able to intercept it, stop it before it happens?
We actually prevented plane crashes, building explosions and people being killed because we were able to know about these plans in advance."
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will head to Europe to help resolve issues related to alleged U.S. espionage abroad and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint counterterrorism activities with the U.S., the chairman of the Senate subcommittee on European affairs said Thursday.
Connecticut Sen. Chris Murphy said he spoke to members of the European Parliament and others this week and is concerned about their threats to stop their involvement in anti-terror organizations due to frustration over the National Security Agency's surveillance.
"It's really important to U.S. national security interests that Europeans remain our supporters of our overall counterterrorism efforts," Murphy, a Democrat in office in his first term and chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs, said in an interview from Washington.
"And I'm going to Europe to let them know that we must continue to cooperate on counterterrorism despite their anger at these NSA programs."
News that the NSA had collected millions of phone records in Europe worsened relations with some U.S. allies, though the agency's chief said this week that they were inaccurate and reflected a misunderstanding of the metadata that NATO allies collected and shared with the U.S.
Other revelations cited documents released by Snowden showing that the NSA monitored the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel, as well as the phones of some 34 other world leaders.
Director of National Intelligence James Clapper defended espionage against allies as necessary and said it was common on both sides.
Amid the hype, Murphy said his office is organizing a trip by members of Congress, which is expected to take place this year, and that he hopes the delegation will include members of both parties and both chambers.
The names of other participating lawmakers are due to be announced in the coming days.
According to him, the program of the trip is still under development.
While Murphy said the purpose of the trip is to promote better relations, he said some degree of "well-meaning rigidity" would also be shown.
He said European leaders should be honest with their people about what spyware they themselves had used for years.
"While we can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, they also have to accept the fact that we are not the only ones engaged in intelligence activities," Murphy said.
Meanwhile, Mr. Kerry is due to head to the Middle East and Poland this weekend to address the hostility to U.S. strategy in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as U.S. intelligence activities.
