Pawnshop owners in Singapore are doing well, while the middle class is struggling
At a pawnshop in Singapore's Bendemir Mall, Janani Amirthalinga pawns a gold bracelet, ring and earrings to pay for his daughter's schooling.
"My husband and I just bought a house, so all my money is invested there," says Ms. Amirthalinga.
Although she earns S$3000 ($2400) a month as an administrator and her husband also works, the family's monthly income is not enough, she says.
Indeed, demand in various parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is rising – is such that ValueMax, where it conducts its transaction, this week became the third pawnshop listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
A jewelry loan is not just a quick way to get money (S$1300 in Ms. Amirthaling's case), but it's almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Typically, pawnshops in Singapore charge an effective annual interest rate of 17% – just above the 15.4% offered at a branch of United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawnshops have the advantage that they do not require credit checks or proof of salary and can issue loans faster than banks.
Therefore, millions of people across the region are turning to pawn shops as families feel pressured by the rising cost of living and the rapid rise in household debt and consumer debt.
After five years of sustained growth in the wake of the global financial crisis and cheap credit fueled by loose monetary policy in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to pawnshops to compensate for declining incomes as their economies slow.
This week, Standard & Poor's, a rating agency, cited an increase in family leverage, largely due to rising mortgages, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
It said Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore had the highest ratio of household debt to gross domestic product in Asia.
Malaysia topped the list with 80% of GDP, up from 60% in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which this week has barely emerged from the technical recession.
On Thursday, data showed a continued decline in exports and weakening consumer demand.
"The bottom line is that as prices rise, people at the middle and bottom of the [income scale] will look for ways to top up their incomes wherever they can," says Song Seng Woon, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Record high gold prices in the past two years have intensified the rush with which people pawn their personal belongings as they take the opportunity to get paid for their family jewellery.
In Singapore, about 70% of the things laid in the 200 pawnshops of the city-state are gold products.
People say, "The price of gold looks good, let's pawn Grandma's gold chain and get it back next month."
In Thailand, the largest pawnshop operator EasyMoney has seen an increase in the number of customers using its branches in recent months, up to 20%.
The growth in the pawnshop business is such that ValueMax, the operator of the Bendemir branch and 15 other similar ones in Singapore, plans to expand not only in neighboring Malaysia, where it has four stores, but also outside of Asia too, says Yeah Lee Ching, chief executive of ValueMax.
The company will finance the expansion using 60 percent of the S$66 million raised this week through a listing on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
While some lenders have sparked fire of criticism over high interest rates, Ms. Yeah says the pawnshop not only offers cheaper rates than other lenders, it also doesn't increase the debt directly.
"Customers mortgage items they already own, and monetizing personal assets doesn't increase household debt," she says.
The mortgage is gaining increasing public acceptance as a means to obtain short-term, secured funding.
And at the same time, pawnshops are used not only by those categories of people who are in a difficult financial situation.
Wealthy people in Singapore also use ValueMax branches, pawning gold bars or Rolex watches that can yield up to 60 percent of their purchase value in cash.
We see clients from all walks of life.
"They include high net worth individuals who need to borrow money for a short period of time for commercial projects or investments, or small businesses who need to overcome temporary monetary difficulties," says Ms. Yeah.
Sometimes they just need the money very quickly.
