Do you have a black box in your car?
While American road designers are trying to find money to repair the crumbling highway system, many are beginning to see the solution in a small black box neatly attached to the dashboard of your car.
These devices, which track every mile a motorist travels and relay that information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt by Washington and state planners to modernize America's outdated highway funding system.
The usually boring highway planning arena has unexpectedly spawned intense debate and colorful alliances.
Libertarians joined environmental groups in lobbying for the government to use small boxes to track the number of miles you drive and even possibly where you pass them — and then use that information when compiling tax bills.
The tea party movement is in shock.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and raises a number of questions regarding privacy.
And although Congress cannot yet agree whether to continue or not, several states are not going to wait.
They wonder how, over the next decade, they can move to a system where drivers pay for every mile of road they drive.
Thousands of motorists have already taken these black boxes for testing, some of which have a satellite tracking function.
This is really necessary for our country.
"This is not an issue on which we can have the right to choose," said Hassan Ihrata, executive director of the Southern California Government Association, which is preparing plans to start tracking the miles every California motorist passes by state authorities by 2025.
There will be changes in how we pay those taxes.
The technology for this is already there.
The need for this is exacerbated by the lack of funds from the Government Highway Construction Fund, funded by the taxes that Americans pay at gas stations.
Americans no longer buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars travel more miles per gallon.
The federal tax itself, 18.4 cents a gallon, hasn't gone up in 20 years.
Politicians do not want to raise the tax even by one cent at high gasoline prices.
"A gasoline tax just can't be maintained," said Lee Mannich, a transportation policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
In his state, 500 tracking devices were recently installed on cars to test the pay-per-parity system.
"This will be the best alternative in the long run," he said.
Nerds call this the user's payroll.
Not surprisingly, this idea attracts urban liberals, since with the help of taxes it will be possible to change the nature of travel to reduce traffic congestion and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
Planners in California are looking at the system as they develop strategies to meet targets set by the state's ambitious global warming laws.
But Rep. Bill Shuster (R-Pa), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he, too, views the system as the most viable long-term alternative.
Free-market advocates at reason are also thrilled that they will force drivers to pay for every mile.
"It's not just a tax that's going to go into a black hole," said Adrian Moore, vice president of political affairs at Reason.
People directly pay for what they get.
The move is also backed by two former U.S. transportation ministers, who in 2011 urged Congress to move toward a pardon.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have involved about 10,000 vehicles.
However, House leaders rejected the proposal because of concerns from rural lawmakers representing voters who often have to travel miles in their daily lives to get to work or the city.
Several states and cities, however, are following this path on their own.
The greatest enthusiasm is shown in Oregon, where 5,000 drivers are involved in participating in the largest experiment in the country.
These drivers will soon pay the state for miles of mileage instead of gasoline tax.
In Nevada, the pilot project has already been completed.
In New York, it is being considered.
Illinois will try it out on a limited basis involving trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transportation departments of 17 East Coast states (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is exploring how they can make those changes.
This concept has not been universally accepted.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer cars were recently equipped with these devices, drivers were concerned that the government could track their every move.
"Concerns about big brother and things like that are big of a concern," said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn't what people wanted.
As the tests were in full swing, the Nevada chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union warned on its website, "It's not hard to turn these devices into full-scale surveillance devices."
There is no need to create a huge, cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably expand to store records of the daily movements of individual citizens.
Nevada is one of several states where there is a difficult search for low-cost technology that would allow state authorities to keep a record of the miles a car travels, but without information about the place and time.
If you can do that, Khan said, society will feel more relaxed.
The search for this technology has led some state agencies to a small young company in California called True Mileage.
Initially, this company was not engaged in assisting in the collection of taxes of the state.
It sought to enter the emerging market for a type of auto insurance in which drivers pay based on mileage.
But the devices it tests attract road designers because they don't use GPS and provide a limited amount of information that is periodically downloaded via a modem.
"People will be more likely to do this if you don't track their speed and track their location," said Ryan Morrison, chief executive of True Mileage.
There have been a few big bugs in some of these state pilot programs.
There are much less expensive and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, designers are experimenting with giving drivers different options.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they may ditch the device altogether, opting instead to pay a fixed fee based on the average number of miles that all residents of the state travel.
Elsewhere, they hope to sell the idea to a wary public by forcing devices to do more, not less.
In New York City, transportation officials are seeking to develop a tax device that will also accept parking meter payments, provide "pay as you drive" insurance, and collect a pool of real-time speed data from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
"Motorists will be attracted to participate in the benefits that they will be offered," the urban design document says.
Some transport system designers, however, wonder if all the talk of a pay per pay is just a huge distraction.
At the San Francisco Bay Area City Transportation Commission, officials say Congress could very easily overcome the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by raising taxes on gasoline.
An additional lump sum or annual tax could be levied on hybrid car drivers and others whose vehicles don't use a lot of gasoline to pay their fair share.
"There's no need for radical surgery when all you have to do is take an aspirin," said Randy Rentschler, director of the Law and Public Relations Commission.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers will worry about their privacy and a host of other things.
