At the moment, the state duty on residential real estate in the areas of Westminster, Kensington and Chelsea, which amounted to 708 million pounds in the 2012/13 financial year, already exceeds the total for Northern Ireland, Wales, Scotland, the north-east, north-west, Yorkshire and Humber combined.
Mr Cook said: "Following the increase in the state duty on expensive homes and the introduction of related anti-evasion legislation, it is very difficult to argue that the taxation of high-value real estate is understated regardless of the impact of the outdated municipal tax system."
"But this move could lead some foreign investors to be reluctant to buy property in London or its current owners will not be willing to sell it," he added.
The value of first-class real estate – the top 5–10% of the housing market by price – in London's wealthy south-west belt, which stretches from Fulham to Wimbledon, has risen by a record 11.8% over the past year.
According to a study by Savills, prices in central London continued to show steady growth of 5.6% year-on-year, but they were overshadowed by the actively developing "domestic market" with a surge in prices in the south-west, in the north (7.4%) and in the east (6.5%) of the city.
The next meeting of the Association of Machine Builders of the Tyumen Region was held on the basis of the Yalutorov Automobile Plant.
Within the framework of the event, a presentation of a new line for the production of electrically welded steel pipes was held.
According to denis Gribanov, commercial director of the enterprise, in 2011, with the advent of a new owner, a marketing research was conducted to study the market for steel structures in the Tyumen region.
It turned out that the region consumes more than 50 thousand tons of electrically welded pipes per month.
After that, it was decided to change the profile of the plant and install equipment for their production on it.
Already this year, more than 7 thousand tons of manufactured products have been shipped.
Investments in the plant amounted to more than 120 million rubles, - said Denis Gribanov.
In October, a new mill was launched, which allows to increase the range.
The plant produces both a small profile of pipe, which is used for thermal farming, small forms of construction and in the furniture industry, and a large one for the construction industry.
We plan to reach the level of production of 50 thousand tons of products per year, which will be about 10 percent of its consumption in the Tyumen region.
Despite the transition to another type of activity, the number of employees at the enterprise has not decreased - now it is 157 people, in the plans for the purchase of new equipment - an increase in staff by more than 50 employees.
The company is retraining of personnel, and the necessary specialists are selected from those already available.
Next year, it is planned to introduce a new unit for slitting steel with a thickness of up to five millimeters, which will reduce the cost of production, as well as another mill, with a pipe production rate of up to 47 meters per minute.
By the end of 2014, the company is going to master the production of pipes that are used in the housing and communal services.
The management of the enterprise sets the task to cover up to 70 percent of the needs of the Tyumen region in these products.
Deputy Director of the Department of Investment Policy Leonid Ostroumov, addressing the heads of production, advised to pay more attention to the modernization of machine-building enterprises.
This is also the aim of forms of state support for industry, which include reimbursement of interest rates on loans for the purchase of new equipment and the cost of its leasing.
This year, it is planned to allocate 150 million rubles for these purposes, two-thirds of this amount has already been spent.
The last commission, which will consider subsidy agreements, accepts documents from enterprises until November 15.
In addition, the budget reimburses the costs of participation of local producers in international fairs.
For next year, the budget provides for funds in the amount of 150 million rubles, which can be used to compensate for leasing payments and loans for the purchase of new equipment.
5 million will be allocated for participation in fairs, 3 million - for energy saving programs.
Funds for reimbursement of ordered and paid equipment, which is produced in the south of the Tyumen region for the oil and gas complex, are reduced to 72 million rubles.
According to Leonid Ostroumov, in the future this form of support will cease, since the motive for its introduction was to compensate for the mineral extraction tax that oil companies paid to the regional budget.
Currently, they do not do this and subsidies become direct expenditure obligations of the region.
With this in mind, the regional government considers direct support for industrial enterprises to be a priority, and not to finance the oil industry through them.
Budget assistance will be associated with investment projects that will be implemented in production.
Many heads of enterprises expressed concern about the current situation in relations with oil companies.
The subsidy for the equipment they purchase is a competitive advantage of the industry in the south of the Tyumen region, and if it is canceled, it will be difficult to compete on price with the central part of Russia, where labor is cheaper.
In addition, the issue of the succession of the new owner of TNK-BP , Rosneft, which has not yet placed its orders at Tyumen enterprises, is unclear.
The agreement on the implementation of the Uvat project expires in 2013, and no application for its extension has been received.
Currently, enterprises in the south of the region, which specialize in equipment for the oil and gas sector, cannot form a portfolio of orders for the next year.
It remains an open question whether taxes from oil produced in the Uvat district will go to the regional budget or they will be paid at the place of registration of the new owner of the fields.
