Syria has destroyed its chemical weapons-making equipment, says observation team
Syria has destroyed major chemical weapons and poison gas munitions equipment, an international monitoring group said On Thursday, as violent clashes raged in the north of the country, near one of the sites where toxic substances are believed to be stored.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian activist group said more than 120,000 people had been killed since the country's civil war began nearly three years ago.
The Statement of the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons was made one day before
The 1 November deadline set by the Hague-based organization for Damascus to destroy or "render inoperable" all chemical weapons production facilities and mechanisms for mixing chemicals with poison gas and filling ammunition with them.
The completion of what is essentially the initial stage of destruction is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable that aims to eliminate all of Damascus' chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of the equipment means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
Nevertheless, Damascus has yet to begin the destruction of existing weapons and stockpiles.
The country is believed to have about 1,000 metric tons of chemicals and weapons, including mustard gas and sarin nerve gas.
The announcement came during heavy fighting on Thursday in the town of Safira, which experts say is home to a chemical weapons production facility as well as storage sites, according to the Britain-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights.
An activist group that tracked casualties through a network of activists in Syria said On Thursday it had killed 120,296 people.
Of this number, 61,067 were said to be civilians, including 6365 children.
On the government side, the group said, 29,954 people are members of President Bashar al-Assad's armed forces, 18,678 are pro-government fighters and 187 are Lebanese Hezbollah fighters.
Also among the dead, as stated in the statement, were 2202 army defectors and about 5375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
According to a July 25 UN assessment, 100,000 have died in the conflict since March 2011.
Since then, this figure has not been updated.
The conflict has forced about 2 million people to flee the country.
Assad's forces have been fighting rebels in Safir for weeks, many of them linked to al-Qaeda groups.
The center said there were casualties on both sides on Thursday, but did not provide specific details.
The fighting highlighted the dangers faced by chemical weapons inspectors, driven by the tight deadlines of their mission to rid Syria of a toxic arsenal, in the midst of an ongoing civil war.
In a statement, the OPCW, which works closely with the United Nations, said its team was "now satisfied that it has inspected and seen all critical production items and mixing/refuelling equipment declared by Syria destroyed."
She added that "no additional inspection activities are currently planned."
Earlier this week, inspectors said they had completed the first round of verification work, visiting 21 of the 23 sites declared by Damascus.
They were unable to visit the two sites for security reasons, the inspectors said.
On Thursday, the OPCW said both sites were, according to Syria's statement, "abandoned and ... the chemical weapons programme items in them have been moved to other declared locations that have been verified."
It was not immediately possible to ascertain whether the Safir facility was one of the two sites that OPCW inspectors were unable to visit.
Syria has submitted a plan for the total destruction of its chemical weapons, which is due to be approved next month by the OPCW's executive committee.
"I salute the courage and bravery you have all demonstrated in carrying out the most challenging mission ever undertaken by this organization," the monitoring team's director general, Ahmet Üzümcü, said in a commentary published by the OPCW.
In its third year, the civil war has pitted rebels, mostly Sunni Muslims, against Assad's government and its security forces, which consist of members of its Alawite sect, an offshoot of Shiite Islam.
As for other developments, the center's head, Rami Abdurrahman, said there was a massive explosion on Wednesday at an air defense facility in Syria's coastal province of Latakia.
The cause of the explosion is unknown, he said.
Message: The Obama campaign considered the exclusion of Biden in favor of Hillary Clinton
According to The New York Times, President Barack Obama's closest advisers secretly considered replacing Vice President Joe Biden with Hillary Clinton on the 2012 electoral roll.
This discovery is the most striking sensation of all the expected book by Mark Halperin and John Heilemann about the 2012 campaign "The Stakes Are Doubled: The Game Has Changed 2012".
The Times obtained a copy of the forthcoming book and reported Thursday night that the president's closest aides conducted "sweeping focus group studies and opinion polls in late 2011" to assess whether Biden's exclusion could help raise fading hopes for Obama's re-election.
According to The Times political commentator Jonathan Martin, the book gives a detailed description of the attempt of senior election and White House officials, namely former White House chief of staff Bill Daly, to assess what effect the appointment of former Secretary of State Clinton as vice president will have on the vote.
A possible replacement was a secret closely guarded in the Chicago Campaign and in the Oval Office.
Only six of the president's closest advisers — including Daley, former Obama campaign chairman Jim Messina and former senior White House advisers David Axelrod and David Plunge — knew a replacement was pending.
The book "Stakes Doubled" claims that Daley was the initiator of the attempt to replace Biden despite their "close personal relationship," but ultimately abandoned the move when their data showed that adding Clinton to the ballot list would not "significantly improve Obama's chances."
In an interview with Martin, Daly confirmed that the administration was indeed considering replacing Biden with Clinton.
"I was actively advocating for looking at a lot of things, and that was one of them," Daly told the newspaper.
You have to remember that the president was in terrible shape at the time, so we were like, "Oh my god, what are we going to do?"
While Daly described the study as a "necessary test," Martin told CNN spokesman Anderson Cooper that the campaign had invested a lot in examining whether the move would pay dividends in the vote.
"Campaigns don't spend that amount of money on polls and focus groups unless they take something seriously," Martin said on AK 360.
It is unclear, however, whether Obama knew that his team was exploring the possibility of a replacement.
Martin told CNN that he asked Daley if his then-boss knew about the possible shuffle.
While Daly said he didn't think the president was "aware" of a possible replacement, the former chief of staff acknowledged that Obama "may" did.
Martin added that "The Stakes Are Doubled" does not provide a clear answer to the question of whether the results of the political probe reached the Obama table.
Cooper asked Martin if he seriously thought Obama was unaware of the study of the possibility of removing Biden from the electoral roll.
"Maybe," Martin replied.
