Legislative bans forced Russians to drink less beer
Russian brewers are in a bad mood.
According to their estimates, beer consumption in the country next year will remain at the same level, and this is at best.
Although businessmen initially counted on growth.
After all, this year is going badly for them: sales fell by 7 percent.
All this was told by the head of one of the largest brewing companies in the country, Chairman of the Council of the Union of Russian Brewers Isaac Sheps at the III annual conference of the Adam Smith Institute "Consumer Goods in Russia", which has just ended in Moscow.
It discussed state regulation of the market.
From 2008 to 2012, the Russian beer market has already declined by 18 percent, as in recent years the country has seen a significant increase in the regulation of the brewing industry in terms of the production and turnover of beer - a drink with a small alcohol content, - Sheps told the audience.
In no country in the world is there such a strict restriction of the beer market, the unpredictable introduction of more and more illogical bans, which are allegedly justified by the fight against alcohol abuse.
The brewer complained that many legislative prohibitions designed to reduce the level of alcohol abuse do not have a special impact, however, new initiatives are constantly emerging.
Beer producers were hit the hardest by the ban imposed this year on the sale of alcohol in kiosks.
"We immediately lost 35,000 consumers," Isaac Sheps said.
Brewers have two predictions for next year.
Optimistic is the one that Sheps was talking about: sales of the foamy drink will remain at the same level.
Pessimistic - will fall by another 2-3 percent.
To preserve their profits, businessmen are forced to move away from varieties designed for the mass consumer to the "premium" class: beer will become less, but it will cost more.
Meanwhile, the radical consequences of falling sales with a small amount of alcohol are not yet visible.
"According to my observations, the level of alcoholism remains approximately at the same level," said narcologist Alexei Sotnikov.
True, the share of patients who use surrogates of strong drinks, as well as those who are "hooked" on alcohol-containing tonic drinks like "Jaguar", has increased, whereas ten years ago it was "beer" alcoholism that prevailed.
What will the construction of TPU in Moscow lead to?
Every year, the city authorities promise to equip more and more transport hubs (TPU).
By 2020, it is planned to put into operation 255 TPU.
What the project actually turns out to be, our correspondent understood.
A couple of months ago, a construction fence appeared near the Smolenskaya metro station of the Arbatsko-Pokrovskaya line.
The inscription stated that the arrangement of a transport and interchange hub was underway.
All this was very strange, because near the "Smolenskaya" no ground transport stops and, therefore, it is impossible to change to it.
To get to the nearest trolleybus stop on the Garden Ring, you need to overcome about 130 meters, including a ground crossing through Karmanitsky Lane.
Now Smolenskaya has almost everything finished.
The flower stall disappeared, the newspaper stand was dismantled, and the asphalt in front of the entrance was replaced by paving stones.
That's the whole transport hub.
Transport and interchange hubs are flat and capital, - the press service of the metropolitan Department of Transport explains.
There are no capital TPU yet.
And flat ones involve the construction of parking lots, the withdrawal of retail facilities that interfere with the movement of passengers, the creation of small architectural forms and landscaping.
Actually, planar TPU is not even engaged in transport workers, but professional landscapers from the Department of Capital Repairs of the City of Moscow.
A transport hub is not necessarily a complex structure," explains Mikhail Blinkin, Director of the Institute of Transport Economics and Transport Policy at the Higher School of Economics.
Sometimes a roof over your head and a scoreboard announcing the time of arrival of transport are enough.
For example, at the Yasenevo metro station, a full-fledged planar interchange hub was recently opened.
Albeit without canopies, but with intercepting parking lots and scoreboards indicating when the bus will arrive.
But in pursuit of quantity, officials write down everything in TPU.
Back in 2011, the mayor's office planned to build 151 nodes for everything, of which 59 with capital construction.
Now the plans until 2020 include as many as 255 TPU.
Of these, half a hundred promise to pass this year.
Although the city has a program for the development of TPU, there are no qualitative criteria, - says Alexander Morozov, co-chairman of the public organization "City and Transport".
They report on the number of objects, but the quality of transplantation at each of them often deteriorates.
According to the expert, there should be two criteria: firstly, a reduction in transplant time, and secondly, convenience.
First of all, the ability to change the mode of transport without going out in the rain.
In Moscow, when arranging TPU, sometimes it turns out exactly the opposite.
A vivid example of the metro "VDNKh".
Previously, suburban buses from the Yaroslavl highway came to the square in front of the main entrance to the All-Russian Exhibition Center.
Now their stops have been moved to the opposite side of Yaroslavka to Kosmonavtov Street.
Farther from the metro, much farther from the monorail, but closer to residential buildings.
It is for nothing that the residents did not want the bus station under the windows and complained to all possible authorities.
With the capital TPU in Moscow, somehow it did not immediately work.
The first of them began to be built about five years ago near the metro station "Planernaya".
The project was intended to be exemplary.
And indeed, it turned out to be an example of how the interchange hub, given to investors, turns into a banal shopping center.
No, there are platforms for buses, a canopy so as not to go from the metro in the rain, and three floors of parking lots.
True, Khimki trolleybuses No. 202 and No. 203 in the Moscow TPU were not given a place in principle.
They were pushed away from the subway like strangers.
But there is more space for trade.
There are 32 stores of clothes alone, and in general there is almost everything - from pet products to a car dealership.
Well, in fact, what if one of the bus passengers needs to buy a new car on the road?
For some reason, when we build a capital TPU, we always get a shopping center.
Recently, the situation reached its logical conclusion, when it was decided to give part of the parking lot to the market.
Now on the third floor of the TPU "Planernaya" among the parking spaces marked on the floor there is a brisk trade.
Vegetables, spices, Chinese jeans, non-Russian speech and security guards looking angrily at our photographer.
The interchange hub finally turned into a bazaar.
The fact is that earlier the metro station "Planernaya" had a market, but it was demolished.
And in the prefecture, the traders were pitied and allowed into the intercepting parking lot of the interchange hub.
Still, due to high prices, it is always empty.
The funny thing is that the market was demolished in order to build it in its place ... new planar TPU.
Such a castling.
At the Kaluzhskaya metro station, the approach distance from the metro lobby to the bus was 50 meters, - says Alexander Morozov.
After the construction of the shopping center, allegedly TPU, the distance increased to 170 meters.
To get on the bus, you need to go through the entire shopping center.
After 10 p.m., when it is closed, you have to go around it in the open air.
However, the structures on the "Planernaya" and "Kaluzhskaya" will soon seem like flowers.
In mid-September, the urban planning and land commission of the mayor's office approved planning decisions for the first eight capital TPU.
Four of them will be 25-storey, not counting two or three underground tiers.
The main monster will grow at the Tushino metro station, it will have 418.7 thousand square meters. meters of area.
Representatives of the Directorate of Railway Stations of Russian Railways, responsible for the construction of TPU near the metro, have already told reporters: shops, hotels and apartments will be located in future high-rise buildings.
At the same time, officials assure that multi-level parking lots will occupy from a third to a half of the area.
Let's take "people's" garages as an example.
For example, a garage for 258 cars, which was recently built on International Street, has an area of 8,015 square meters. meters.
So, for parking for 2.6 thousand cars at Petrovsko-Razumovskaya, you will need about 80 thousand "squares".
This is less than a third of the colossus that they are going to build there.
Let one or two floors go to all sorts of platforms for buses.
At least 150 thousand square meters of commercial real estate remain.
And that, for a moment, is almost two GUMs.
If railway workers build capital TPU near stations and railway stations, then the rest of the sites will be mastered by metro workers.
They, too, promised that there would be many "functional facilities," including hotels, offices and even gyms.
By the way, the Department of Property of the city of Moscow recently told journalists that they are developing a draft resolution according to which investors will be able to apply for a plot for TPU to officials directly.
Without any contests.
Because, they say, transport issues for the city are a priority.
The ideal TPU is, for example, the stations "Harvard" in Boston or "Spadina" in Toronto, - Alexander Morozov is sure.
There, trolleybuses and trams descend underground to the metro level and the approach distance from the metro car to the tram is only 50 meters without going outside.
There is no extra trade around.
But Moscow officials are thrown to extremes.
Either we will not build anything, or we will build 25 floors with offices and apartments.
Oil fell in price to $ 96 per barrel.
Oil prices continued to fall on Friday as worries about the formation of large inventories overshadowed a message showing that China's energy-intensive manufacturing sector was gaining momentum.
The benchmark grade of US oil in december delivery fell by 14 cents, and its price was $ 96.24 per barrel in late morning European time in electronic trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
On Thursday, the contract fell by 39 cents, which in total amounted to a drop in the price for October by 5.8 percent.
Rich oil reserves have affected its value in recent weeks.
The Energy Department on Wednesday said U.S. inventories had increased by 4.1 million barrels over the past week.
In five weeks, reserves were replenished by more than 25 million barrels.
But on Friday, there was an indication of a possible increase in demand, judging by two reports about the Chinese industry, which showed a surge in its activity.
This indicates that China's economic recovery may continue to gain strength after the growth rate in the third quarter rose to 7.8 percent after a twenty-year low in the previous quarter.
Brent crude, an international benchmark also used by U.S. refiners, fell 26 cents to $108.58 a barrel on the Intercontinental Exchange in London.
