Bombardier's profits decline with a drop in deliveries and the number of orders for aircraft
Bombardier Corporation, a Canadian plane and train maker, reported a 15 percent decline in net profit on Thursday, impacted by a reduced number of aircraft orders and deliveries in the third quarter and contract problems at its rail division.
Montreal-based Bombardier also did not release any data on flight tests of its newest CSeries aircraft and did not provide new information on whether ambitious plans to put the aircraft into commercial operation by next September will be fulfilled.
After the first flight of the prototype aircraft, which took place about a month and a half ago, he flew only three more times, which raises questions about whether the test stage is on schedule.
The results fell short of forecasts and led to a drop in stocks of more than 8 per cent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerxen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, lowered his estimate Thursday from "above market average" to "market average" due to the belief that stock growth is limited in the next quarter or two.
"While the decline in aircraft deliveries was generally predictable, we are certainly disappointed with the transportation division's profit figures," Doerxen said in a stock market review.
We believe that Bombardier will receive new orders for CSeries as the flight test program continues.
However, unless new orders are announced in the coming months, we assume the market will become more skeptical about the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will allow it to win a place in the lower price segment of the market, which is now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first prototype of the aircraft was presented in March and flew for the first time in September after several months of delay.
However, there are not too many firm orders for CSeries so far - 177, as potential buyers are waiting for the results of flight tests to check the company's statements about the fuel efficiency and potential efficiency of the new liner.
In total, there are now 403 orders and agreements with 15 customers and operators.
Chief Executive Officer Pierre Baudouin was confident that Bombardier would reach its goal of 300 firm orders by the time the first aircraft was put into commercial operation.
On Thursday, executives also assured analysts and media outlets that the program was moving forward with plan.
"The test model of the aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected," Bauduan said during a conference call, adding that ground tests and software updates were scheduled for the aircraft's downtime.
All manufacturers plan the tests differently.
We decided to hold the first flight and take a break for updates, so we did.
This will happen throughout the flight test program.
The second of the five test samples is due to fly in the coming weeks and all the others will soon follow, the company said.
And yet analysts are skeptical of the claim that the first customer will be able to start operating the CSeries aircraft 12 months after its first flight.
Bombardier said it was estimating the commissioning date and would provide new information in the next few months.
"This slow pace of flight testing – while apparently in line with Bombardier's internal schedule – reinforces our view that commissioning will be pushed backed up to the first quarter of 2015," Doerxen said.
In the third quarter ended September 30, Bombardier's net income fell to $147 million, or 8 cents per share, from $172 million, or 9 cents per share, last year.
Adjusted earnings per share remained the same at 9 cents.
Gross revenue decreased slightly - from $ 4.2 to $ 4.1 billion.
Analysts had expected earnings of 10 cents per share and gross revenue of $4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I/B/E/S.
The world's fourth-largest aircraft maker said it delivered 45 aircraft for the quarter, down from the previous year's 57.
The total number of orders fell from 83 to 26 aircraft.
The Aerospace Division's order book was $32.9 billion as of Sept. 30, unchanged from Dec. 31.
"In the aerospace field, the results were in line with our goals, but the low number of orders received and the overall market conditions were an unpleasant factor," Bauduan said.
Gross revenue for aerospace fell 13 percent to $2 billion.
Bombardier, the world's largest train manufacturer, said gross revenue in the sector rose nearly 11 percent to $2.1 billion.
The order book in the transportation division was $32.6 billion as of Sept. 30, up slightly from Dec. 31.
The revenues of the transport division were negatively affected by problems with the execution of several large contracts.
Management said a new development plan would be presented in the fourth quarter.
Shares of Bombardier, which also announced that Google Chief Financial Officer Patrick Pichette will join the board of directors, fell 8.5 percent to C$4.83 in mid-Thursday trading.
Brazilian company Embraer SA, the world's third-largest commercial aircraft manufacturer and closest competitor Bombardier, reported a 10 percent decline in quarterly revenue on Thursday.
