Two YMCA staff members charged with sexual offences even before charges against Jonathan Lord, royal commission learned
Two YMCA NSW employees were charged with sexual offences against children before charges were filed in 2011 against Jonathan Lord, an employee of a caring facility in Karingbach, the Royal Commission on Child Sexual Abuse said.
But in an opening statement, the commission said it had "never dealt with cases of child sexual abuse within its organization."
Chief Executive Officer Philip Hare was asked about one case in which a YMCA employee was charged with child pornography offences and another case in which a gym instructor at YMCA Caringbah Hall was convicted of sexual offences against children under his care in 1991.
Mr Hare told Gail Furness, the lawyer assisting the commission, that he was aware of the first case but was unaware of the second.
He acknowledged that the YMCA also made an inaccuracy in its opening speech to the commission, arguing that "there have been external YMCA reviews that have recognized that the YMCA is at the forefront of child safety."
The evidence presented to the commission suggests that the YMCA has been notified that it has received the second from the end of four possible assessments based on the results of a quality audit performed by the Department of Education and Communities in August this year.
Mr. Hare, who joined the YMCA when he was 21, admitted that he and the lower management had made a mistake by hiring Lord and had failed to ensure that staff were clearly aware of their obligations regarding reporting violations of the child safety policy.
Earlier this year, Lord was convicted of sex crimes against 12 boys during his two years at the YMCA.
He was jailed for at least six years.
But Mr. Hare rejected suggestions that the YMCA's corporate ethics prevented employees from reporting Lorde's child safety violations.
Officers testified that they observed abuses, including that Lord was alone with the children, personally cared for them, put them in his lap, said he loved one of them and allowed them to play with his mobile phone.
Danielle Oakwell, who was under Lorde's direction and asked to be trained in child protection because she was concerned about his behaviour, testified that she found Jackie Barnut, the child custody manager of the YMCA's Karingbach branch who was Lord's supervisor, "very intimidating and often difficult to access".
The executive director said he did not accept employee explanations that they were embarrassed to report the situation to their superiors.
Rather, he said, their friendship with Lord led them away from the idea of having to report him.
Mr Hare said he had presented his views to the YMCA NSW council that the lesson to organise the "Jonathan Lord incident" was not "about the provision of information" by staff, and the board agreed with him.
Mr. Hare said the decision to force employees to sign confidentiality agreements shortly after the allegations surfaced was made by YMCA CEO of child custody Liam Wheatley.
He said it was designed to prevent damage to the evidence, but at the same time they "overdid it" and the decision was poorly implemented.
The YMCA of New South Wales was not a child-safe organisation during Jonathan Lord's work in it between 2009 and 2011, Child Molestation expert Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University told the commission.
He said there were "serious challenges" in recruiting, selecting, instructing, training and supervising staff.
The hearing has been adjourned until Dec. 20.
