Ben Greenman: Tenth Anniversary of the New York Comedy Festival: The New Yorker
We can safely say that New York is the birthplace of stand-up comedy in America: almost a hundred years ago, pop artist Frank Faye, who worked as an entertainer at the Palace Theater on Broadway, began to tell jokes directly to the public in a colloquial manner.
Faye's innovation was eventually picked up by others, most recently the New York Comedy Festival.
Created and curated by Caroline Hirsch, founder of the stand-up club Carolines, the festival is celebrating its tenth anniversary this year with more than sixty shows in small clubs and large theaters.
"Most of these headliners started at Carolines and then got more success, reached a level where they were already too famous to play at the club," Hirsch said.
We created this festival as a way to continue working with them.
This year's event includes performances by Wanda Sykes, Katie Griffin and Bill Mare, as well as Stand-up for Heroes, an annual music and comedy benefit concert for military veterans at Madison Square Garden, featuring Bruce Springsteen, John Stewart, Roger Waters and Bill Cosby, among others.
With the expansion of the festival, the world of comedy has also expanded.
Several comedians participating in this year's festival have gained popularity in unconventional ways, such as through shows on smaller TV channels like Comedy Central, FX and Spike.
Nick Kroll gained fame thanks to his role in a comedy series on a little-known cable channel (FXX's deliberately scabrous "League" on the theme of fantasy football), and now leads his own sketch show on Comedy Central.
Jenny Slate was included in the cast in both Saturday Night Live and Parks and Recreation, although she is best known for the series of viral videos "Marseille is a shell in shoes."
Both Kroll and Slate, like other young comedians with distinctive styles (the surreally pessimistic Anthony Jeselnick, the crafty, racially focused Kamau Bell), are the result of the decentralized world of American comedy.
One of the highlights of the festival will be David Steinberg's interview with Larry David.
Steinberg began as a stand-up comedian, but later became a successful director in television and film, as well as an unofficial historian of comedy.
From 2005 to 2007, he was the host of a show on TV Land called Sit Down Comedy with David Steinberg.
The meeting will take place at Town Hall in midtown Manhattan.
"This city is definitely the centerpiece of all of Larry's work," Steinberg said.
He told me that when he comes here, he sometimes walks along some street between two houses and thinks: "If I am left with no money at all, maybe I will live here."
